{"title_page": "Logan Ryan", "text_new": "{{short description|American football cornerback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name          = Logan Ryan\n| image         = Logan Ryan 2018 08-09.jpg <!-- Only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people -- see [[WP:NONFREE]]. -->\n| image_size    = 225px\n| alt           = Logan Ryan\n| caption       = Ryan with the Titans in 2018\n| current_team  = New York Jets \n| number        = \n| position      = [[Cornerback]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1991|2|9|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Berlin, New Jersey]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height_ft     = 5\n| height_in     = 11\n| weight_lbs    = 195\n| high_school   = [[Eastern Regional High School|Eastern Regional]]<br/>{{nowrap|([[Voorhees Township, New Jersey]])}}\n| college       = [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]]\n| draftyear     = 2013\n| draftround    = 3\n| draftpick     = 83\n| pastteams     = \n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|2013}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})\n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2019}})\n| status        = \n| highlights    = \n* 2x [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]], [[Super Bowl LI|LI]])\n* First-team All-[[Big East Conference (1979-2013)|Big East]] (2012)\n* First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2012 College Football All-America Team|2012]])\n| statseason  = 2019\n| statweek    = \n| statlabel1  = [[Tackle (football move)|Total tackles]]\n| statvalue1  = 491\n| statlabel2  = [[Quarterback sack|Sacks]]\n| statvalue2  = 11.0\n| statlabel3  = [[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]] \n| statvalue3  = 1\n| statlabel4  = [[Interceptions]]\n| statvalue4  = 17\n| statlabel5  =  [[Fumble|Forced fumbles]] \n| statvalue5  = 8\n| statlabel6  = [[Pass deflections]]\n| statvalue6  = 78\n| nflnew      = loganryan/2540162\n}}\n\n'''Logan Daniel Ryan'''<ref>{{cite web| title=Logan Ryan Pro-Football-Reference Profile |work=rbref.com |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/R/RyanLo00.htm |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.titansonline.com/team/players-roster/logan-ryan/ |title=Logan Ryan |work=Tennessee Titans |access-date= is currently a free agenAugust 24, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> (born February 9, 1991) is an [[American football]] [[cornerback]] who plays for the [[New York Jets]]. He was drafted by the [[New England Patriots]] in the third round of the [[2013 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football|Rutgers]].\n\n==Early years==\nA native of [[Berlin, New Jersey]], Ryan attended [[Eastern Regional High School]] in [[Voorhees, New Jersey]], and played for the Eastern Vikings [[high school football]] team. He was an all-state selection at both cornerback and quarterback. Regarded as a four-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Ryan was ranked the No. 32 cornerback prospect in his class.\n<ref>https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-2130</ref>\n\n==College career==\nRyan played for the [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights football]] team from 2010 to 2012. He was a second-team All-[[Big East Conference (1979-2013)|Big East Conference]] selection as a sophomore in 2011 and was a first-team All-Big East selection as a junior in 2012.\n\nRyan was also named a first-team [[All-American]] by ''[[Pro Football Weekly]]'' in 2012.<ref>[http://www.profootballweekly.com/2012/12/11/pfw-2012-all-america-team PFW 2012 All-America team] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121215122832/http://www.profootballweekly.com/2012/12/11/pfw-2012-all-america-team |date=December 15, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn December 31, 2012, Ryan announced that he would forgo his senior year at Rutgers and declared for the [[2013 NFL Draft]].<ref>http://www.nj.com/rutgersfootball/index.ssf/2012/12/rutgers_cornerback_logan_ryan_2.html</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nComing out of Rutgers, Ryan was projected to be a third round by the majority of NFL draft experts and scouts. He attended the NFL combine and completed all of the required combine and positional drills. On March 13, 2013, Ryan participated at Rutger's pro day along with were [[Marcus Cooper]], [[Duron Harmon]], [[Steve Beauharnais]], [[Mark Harrison (American football)|Mark Harrison]], [[Brandon Jones (cornerback)|Brandon Jones]], [[Jawan Jamison]], [[Khaseem Greene]], and seven others. NFLDraftScout.com ranked him the 13th best cornerback prospect in the draft.<ref>{{cite web| title=Logan Ryan, DS #13 CB, Rutgers| URL=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/pyrnotes.php?pyid=89766&draftyear=2013&genpos=CB| accessdate=November 9, 2017| website=nfldraftscout.com}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-videos/0ap2000000154050/2013-Combine-workout-Logan-Ryan Logan Ryan's NFL Combine Workout]\n}}\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 5\n|    height in = 11\u215b\n|       weight = 191\n|         dash = 4.56\n|    ten split = 1.58\n| twenty split = 2.65\n|      shuttle = 4.06\n|   cone drill = 6.69\n|     vertical = 32\u00bd\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 8\n|        bench = 14\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 31\u215c\n|    hand span = 9\u215d\n|         note = All value from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=89766&draftyear=2013&genpos=CB| title=*Logan Ryan, DS #13 CB, Rutgers| accessdate=May 24, 2017| website=nfldraftscout.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.nfl.com/draft/2013/profiles/logan-ryan?id=2540162| title=NFL Draft Scout: Logan Ryan| accessdate=May 24, 2017| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===New England Patriots===\nThe [[New England Patriots]] selected Ryan in the third round (83rd overall) of the [[2013 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/draft.htm |title=2013 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> He was the 14th cornerback drafted in 2013.\n\n====2013 season: Rookie year====\nOn May 16, 2013, the New England Patriots signed Ryan to a four-year, $2.77 million contract that includes a signing bonus of $563,252.<ref name=\"Spotrac\">{{cite web| title=Spotrac.com: Logan Ryan contract| URL=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/tennessee-titans/logan-ryan-12364/| accessdate=November 9, 2017| website=spotrac.com}}</ref>\n\nRyan competed for a starting cornerback job behind [[Alfonzo Dennard]], [[Aqib Talib]], [[Kyle Arrington]], and [[Ras-I Dowling]]. Head coach [[Bill Belichick]] named him the fourth cornerback on the Patriots' depth chart to begin the 2013 season, behind Dennard, Talib, and Arrington.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots' depth chart: 10/01/2013| URL=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/148/NE| accessdate=November 9, 2017| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nRyan made his NFL debut in the Patriots' season-opening 23\u201321 victory over the [[2013 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080buf.htm |title=New England Patriots at Buffalo Bills - September 8th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> During Week 6 against the [[2013 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], Ryan made his first NFL start, helping the Patriots earn a 30\u201327 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310130nwe.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at New England Patriots - October 13th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On October 20, 2013, Ryan made four solo tackles, a pass deflection, and his first NFL interception off a pass from [[2013 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] quarterback [[Geno Smith]] during a 27\u201330 loss. He returned the interception for a 79-yard touchdown, marking the first of his career.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310200nyj.htm |title=New England Patriots at New York Jets - October 20th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The following week, he recorded a season-high four solo tackles, defended a pass, forced a fumble, and was credited with the first 1\u00bd sacks of his career after taking down [[Ryan Tannehill]] in a 27\u201317 victory over the [[2013 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310270nwe.htm |title=Miami Dolphins at New England Patriots - October 27th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn November 24, 2013, Ryan was named the starter over Alfonzo Dennard, who had been battling a knee injury. He recorded four combined tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass by [[Peyton Manning]] during a 34\u201331 victory over the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201311240nwe.htm |title=Denver Broncos at New England Patriots - November 24th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The following week, he started in place of Dennard, who was inactive, and recorded three solo tackles, two pass deflections, and intercepted a pass attempt by [[Case Keenum]] during the Patriots' 34\u201331 victory over the [[2013 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]].<ref>{{cite web|\ntitle=NFL Game Center: Week 13-2013: New England Patriots @ Houston Texans| URL=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2013120109/2013/REG13/patriots@texans| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=NFL.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Alfonzo Dennard Injury: Updates on Patriots CB's Knee Surgery and Return Date| url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1858382-alfonzo-dennard-injury-updates-on-patriots-cbs-knee-surgery-and-return-date| accessdate=November 9, 2017| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Tim Daniels| date=November 20, 2013}}</ref> On December 22, 2013, he recorded a tackle, a season-high two pass deflections, and intercepted [[Joe Flacco]] twice, as the Patriots defeated the [[2013 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] 41\u20137.<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web| title=N Player stats: Logan Ryan| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/loganryan/2540162/gamelogs?season=2013| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nRyan finished his rookie year with 35 combined tackles (29 solo), 1.5 sacks, five interceptions, ten passes defended, and a forced fumble in 16 games and seven starts.<ref name = \"pats stats\">http://www.nfl.com/player/loganryan/2540162/profile</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\n[[File: Logan Ryan.JPG|thumb|Ryan in 2014]]\nRyan competed against Alfonzo Dennard, [[Darrelle Revis]], Kyle Arrington, and [[Brandon Browner]] for the vacant starting cornerback position left by the departure of Aqib Talib. He was named the third cornerback on the Patriots' depth chart to begin the regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots' depth chart: 10/01/2014|  URL=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/164/NE| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nOn September 14, 2014, Ryan earned his first start of the season after Dennard was unable to play due to a shoulder injury. Ryan recorded three combined tackles, defended two passes, and intercepted [[Teddy Bridgewater]] during a 30\u20137 victory over the [[2014 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409140min.htm |title=New England Patriots at Minnesota Vikings - September 14th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots Injury Report: Siliga Still Out, Collins, Dennard, Gronk Still Limited | URL=https://www.boston.com/sports/extra-points/2014/09/25/patriots_injury_report_siliga_still_out_collins_de/amp| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=Boston.com| author=Jeremy Gottlieb}}</ref> In the next game, he recorded a season-high four solo tackles and deflected a pass during a 16\u20139 win against the [[2014 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409210nwe.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at New England Patriots - September 21st, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In the regular-season finale, Ryan collected a season-high five combined tackles during a 9\u201317 loss to the [[2014 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412280nwe.htm |title=Buffalo Bills at New England Patriots - December 28th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> He was named the starter after Alfonzo Dennard suffered a [[hamstring]] injury earlier in the week.<ref>{{cite web| title=Friday Injury Report: Jonas Gray and Alfonzo Dennard Out, 15 Questionable| URL=https://www.patspulpit.com/platform/amp/2014/12/26/7452075/friday-injury-report-jonas-gray-and-alfonzo-dennard-out-15|access-date=November 10, 2014| website=patspulpit.com| author=Bernd Buchmasser| date=December 26, 2014}}</ref> \n\nRyan finished his second professional season with 42 combined tackles (29 solo), six pass deflections, and two interceptions in 16 games and six starts.<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n\nThe Patriots finished the season atop the [[AFC East]] with a 12-4 record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2014.htm |title=2014 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On January 10, 2015, Ryan played in his first career playoff game and made one tackle and forced a fumble in a 35\u201331 victory over the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501100nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots - January 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On February 1, 2015, Ryan appeared in [[Super Bowl XLIX]] and made a tackle and pass deflection in a 28\u201324 victory over the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]].<ref name = \"pats stats\"/>\n\n====2015 season====\nRyan competed with [[Malcolm Butler]], [[Justin Green (cornerback)|Justin Green]], [[Bradley Fletcher]], and [[Tarell Brown]] for the vacant starting cornerback positions throughout training camp after Darrelle Revis, Alfonzo Dennard, Kyle Arrington, and Brandon Browner left during the off season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots' Depth chart: 10/01/2015| URL=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/174/NE| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> Head coach [[Bill Belichick]] named him the third cornerback on the depth chart behind Malcolm Butler and Tarell Brown to start the {{NFL Year|2015}} season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots' depth chart: 10/ 01/ 2015| URL=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/176/NE| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week 2 against the [[2015 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Ryan recorded four combined tackles, deflected a pass, and intercepted a pass attempt by [[Tyrod Taylor]] as the Patriots won 40\u201332.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200buf.htm |title=New England Patriots at Buffalo Bills - September 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The following week, he was named the starting cornerback after Tarell Brown was unable to play due to a foot injury.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots starting CB Tarell Brown placed on IR| URL=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/patriots-tarell-brown-placed-on-injured-reserve/amp/| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=cbssports.com| author=Rotowire| date=October 18, 2015}}</ref> Ryan made four combined tackles during the 51\u201317 win against the [[2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509270nwe.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at New England Patriots - September 27th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> During Week 5 against the [[2015 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], Ryan recorded three combined tackles, a pass deflection, and intercepted a pass attempt by quarterback [[Brandon Weeden]] during a 30\u20136 road victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510110dal.htm |title=New England Patriots at Dallas Cowboys - October 11th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, he recorded a season-high nine combined tackles and defended the pass during a 34\u201327 victory over the [[2015 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510180clt.htm |title=New England Patriots at Indianapolis Colts - October 18th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> He was named the indefinite starting cornerback for the remainder of the season after the game, replacing Tarell Brown who was placed on injured reserve.\n\nRyan finished the 2015 season with 74 combined tackles (58 solo), a then career-high 14 pass deflections, and four interceptions in 16 games and 14 starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.csnne.com/new-england-patriots/new-england-patriots-logan-ryan-elevates-his-game-commitment-film-study# |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 28, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301091922/http://www.csnne.com/new-england-patriots/new-england-patriots-logan-ryan-elevates-his-game-commitment-film-study# |archive-date=March 1, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Patriots finished atop the AFC East with a 12-4 record and earned a playoff berth.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2015.htm |title=2015 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On January 16, 2016, he made his first NFL postseason start and recorded nine combined tackles during a 27\u201320 victory over the [[2015 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601160nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Kansas City Chiefs at New England Patriots - January 16th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The following week, he made five solo tackles and defended a pass, as the Patriots lost on the road 18\u201320 to the [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] in the AFC Championship.<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n\n====2016 season====\nRyan was named the starting cornerback, alongside Malcolm Butler, for the second consecutive season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: New England Patriots' depth chart: 10/01/2016| URL=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/188/NE| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2016, Ryan recorded a career-high 17 combined tackles in the Patriots' 0\u201316 loss to the [[2016 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610020nwe.htm |title=Buffalo Bills at New England Patriots - October 2nd, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> Ryan was delegated to the third cornerback on the depth chart for Weeks 7-8 after [[Eric Rowe]] emerged as the starter after being inactive for the first five games while rehabbing an ankle injury.<ref>{{cite web| title=In this corner . . . who? Eric Rowe or Logan Ryan?| URL=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/patriots/2016/11/11/this-corner-who-eric-rowe-logan-ryan/dWCXfr4fihSXNx4UrxIBnK/amp.html| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=bostonglobe.com| author=Nora Princiotti| date=November 11, 2016}}</ref> During Week 11, Ryan was moved to starting nickelback after struggling against receivers as the starting outside cornerback. Rowe replaced starting outside cornerback as Ryan took over slot coverage duties from [[Patrick Chung]]. He developed into a viable starting nickelback and gave up only four receptions on 11 targets through Weeks 11-12.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots CB Logan Ryan is finding a new home in the slot| URL=https://www.patspulpit.com/platform/amp/2016/12/4/13827576/patriots-cb-logan-ryan-is-finding-a-new-home-in-the-slot-butler-belichick-rowe| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=patspulpit.com| author=Rich Hill| date=December 4, 2016}}</ref> Through Weeks 11-16, he was called for one penalty and allowed no touchdown receptions and only 11 catches on 30 pass attempts.<ref>{{cite web| title=Patriots Cornerbacks Have Locked Down Receivers Since Week 10 Loss| URL=https://www.nesn.com/2016/12/patriots-cornerbacks-have-locked-down-receivers-since-week-10-loss/amp/| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=nesn.com| author=Doug Kyed| date=December 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 18, 2016, Ryan recorded seven solo tackles, deflected a pass, and intercepted quarterback [[Trevor Siemian]] as the Patriots defeated the [[2016 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] on the road by a score of 16\u20133.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612180den.htm |title=New England Patriots at Denver Broncos - December 18th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In the regular-season finale, Ryan made seven combined tackles, defended a pass, and intercepted [[Ryan Tannehill]] during a 35\u201314 victory over the [[2016 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201701010mia.htm |title=New England Patriots at Miami Dolphins - January 1st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRyan finished the season with a then-career-high 92 combined tackles (74 solo), 11 pass deflections, two interceptions, a sack, and a forced fumble while appearing in all 16 games and starting 13. He started six games as the outside cornerback with Malcolm Butler and started seven games as nickelback.<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n\nThe Patriots finished atop the AFC East with a 14-2 record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2016.htm |title=2016 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> On January 14, 2017, he started at nickelback in the Divisional Round of the playoffs against the [[2016 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] and collected seven combined tackles, three pass deflections, a sack, and intercepted a pass attempt by quarterback [[Brock Osweiler]] in the 34\u201316 victory.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Centee: Week 19-2016: Houston Texans @ New England Patriots| URL= http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2017011401/2016/POST19/texans@patriots| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=NFL.com}}</ref> On February 5, 2017, Ryan started in the [[Super Bowl LI]] for the first time of his career and recorded six combined tackles as the Patriots defeated the [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] 34\u201328 in overtime after trailing by 25 points in the third quarter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm|title=Super Bowl LI - New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons - February 5th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=September 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tennessee Titans===\nOn March 10, 2017, the [[Tennessee Titans]] signed Ryan to a three-year, $30 million contract with $12 million guaranteed and a signing bonus of $2 million.<ref name=\"Spotrac\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Logan Ryan inks three-year deal with Titans|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000792128/article/logan-ryan-inks-threeyear-deal-with-titans|website=NFL.com|date=March 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Titans Agree to Terms with Former Patriots CB Logan Ryan|url=http://www.titansonline.com/news/article-4/Titans-Agree-to-Terms-with-Former-Patriots-CB-Logan-Ryan/e93778fc-e2f4-4bca-b478-f2c7ab104bd6|author=Wyatt, Jim|website=TitansOnline.com|date=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\nRyan was named the Titans' starting cornerback, opposite [[Adoree' Jackson]], to begin the regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: Tennessee Titans' depth chart: 10/01/2017| URL=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/200/TEN| accessdate=November 10, 2017| website=Ourlads.com}}</ref> Ryan made his Titans' debut in the season-opener against the [[2017 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]] and recorded a tackle and forced a fumble during a 16\u201326 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100oti.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 10th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> Two weeks later, he earned a season-high six solo tackles and a season-high three pass deflections, as the Titans defeated the [[2017 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] 33\u201327.<ref name=\"stats\"/>\n\nRyan finished his first season with the Titans with 62 tackles, a forced fumble, and 11 pass deflections.<ref>{{cite web|title=Logan Ryan Stats|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/15861/logan-ryan|website=ESPN.com|access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Titans finished second in the [[AFC South]] with a 9-7 record and qualified for the playoffs. In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: Tennessee Titans 22, Kansas City Chiefs 21|Wild Card Round]], the Titans played the [[2017 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]]. In a 22-21 road victory, Ryan had three solo tackles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801060kan.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Tennessee Titans at Kansas City Chiefs \u2013 January 6th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=January 30, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 35, Tennessee Titans 14|Divisional Round]] against the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], he had 12 tackles (10 solo) in the 35\u201314 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots \u2013 January 13th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=February 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\nRyan entered the 2018 season as a starting cornerback alongside [[Adoree' Jackson]] and former Patriots teammate [[Malcolm Butler]]. He started the first 14 games before suffering a broken fibula in a Week 15 17-0 road victory against the [[2018 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Logan Ryan will miss the rest of the season after breaking leg|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/12/17/logan-ryan-will-miss-the-rest-of-the-season-after-breaking-leg/|author=Gantt, Darin|work=Pro Football Talk|publisher=NBC Sports|date=December 17, 2018}}</ref> He was placed on injured reserve on December 18, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titans Promote CB Kenneth Durden, and Place CB Logan Ryan on Injured Reserve|url=https://www.titansonline.com/news/titans-promote-cb-kenneth-durden-and-place-cb-logan-ryan-on-injured-reserve|author=Wyatt, Jim|website=TitansOnline.com|date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRyan finished the season with 76 tackles, eight passes defensed, no interceptions, and a career-high four sacks, which led all defensive backs at the time of his injury.\n\n====2019 season====\n[[File:Logan Ryan.png|thumb|Ryan after intercepting a pass thrown by former teammate [[Tom Brady]] and returning it for a touchdown in the AFC Wild Card game against the [[New England Patriots]] ]]\nRyan returned from his injury in time for the Titans' season opener against the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]]. In that game, he made eight tackles, sacked [[Baker Mayfield]] 1.5 times, and intercepted a pass from him once as the Titans won 43\u201313.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127928 |title=Mariota, Titans sack Mayfield, hyped Browns 43-13 in opener |date=8 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he intercepted former Patriots teammate [[Jacoby Brissett]] once as the Titans narrowly lost 19\u201317.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128114 |title=Brissett spoils Titans' opener, rallying Colts to 19-17 win |date=15 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref> During Week 5 against the [[2019 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Ryan recorded a team high nine tackles and sacked [[Josh Allen (quarterback)|Josh Allen]] once in the 14\u20137 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128014 |title=Josh Allen throws 2 TD passes as Bills smother Titans 14-7 |date=6 October 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref> During Week 10 against the [[2019 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], he recorded a team high 13 tackles and three passes defended in the narrow 35\u201332 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127981 |title=Titans rally, spoil Mahomes' return beating Chiefs 35-32 |date=10 November 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nRyan finished the season setting career-highs in tackles with 113, sacks with 4.5, pass deflections with 18, and forced fumbles with four. He also had four interceptions.\n\nOn January 4, 2020, the Titans played in the Wild Card Round of the playoffs where they faced Ryan's former team, the [[2019 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]. In the waning seconds of the game with the Titans leading 14\u201313, and New England on their own 1-yard line, Ryan intercepted a deflected pass from former teammate [[Tom Brady]] (which turned out to be Brady's final pass as a Patriot, as he would not return to the Patriots the following season) and returned it for a 9-yard touchdown. The score secured a 20\u201313 upset in Foxborough, allowing the Titans to play in the Divisional Round of the playoffs for the second time in three years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131036 |title=Derrick Henry, Titans stun Patriots 20-13 in wild-card upset |date=January 4, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> In the Divisional Round against the [[2019 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Ryan recorded a team-high 13 tackles during the 28\u201312 road victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131041 |title=Titans stun Ravens, head to AFC title game with 28-12 win |date=January 11, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n| Team won the Super Bowl\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"4\"| Tackles\n! colspan=\"6\"| Interceptions\n! colspa