scue Foundation (ryananimalfoundation.org). RARF works with animal welfare organizations to promote adoption and provide grants and educational opportunities. Every month on the 26th\u2014the day corresponding to his jersey number\u2014Ryan posts a photo on social media with a dog that is in need of adoption along with the hashtag #ryansmonthlyrescue. Ryan's older brother, Jordan, attended Drexel University and is now an engineer.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.titansonline.com/team/players-roster/logan-ryan/ |title=Logan Ryan |work=Tennessee Titans |access-date=August 24, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121123233026/http://www.scarletknights.com/football/roster/detail.asp?id=4365 Rutgers Scarlet Knights bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130605110424/http://www.patriots.com/team/roster/Logan-Ryan/70f3378f-027b-45b8-a04e-bcbb56781c27 New England Patriots bio]\n*[http://www.titansonline.com/team/roster/Logan-Ryan/c0df9b74-0b31-48cd-8bd1-dd6b9dbabe09 Tennessee Titans bio]\n\n{{Patriots2013DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XLIX}}\n{{Super Bowl LI}}\n{{Tennessee Titans roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ryan, Logan}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football cornerbacks]]\n[[Category:Eastern Regional High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots players]]\n[[Category:People from Berlin, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Rutgers Scarlet Knights football players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Camden County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n", "name_user": "69.120.203.12", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logan_Ryan"}
{"title_page": "Kangal Shepherd Dog", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Anatolian Shepherd Dog}}\n{{original research section|date=November 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox dog breed\n|name     = Kangal Shepherd Dog\n|image    = Varish, Berger d'anatolie, Kangal.jpeg\n|image_alt = \n|image_caption =\n|altname  = Turkish Kangal,\n|nickname = Kangal\n|country  = Sivas, Turkey\n|patronage    = \n|coat         =\n|color        =\n|litter_size  =\n|life_span    =\n|fcigroup   = [[FCI Pinscher and Schnauzer, Molossoid and Swiss Mountain Dog Group|2]]\n|fcisection = 2.2 Molossian: Mountain type\n|fcinum     = 331\n|fcistd     = http://www.fci.be/Nomenclature/Standards/331g02-en.pdf\n|akcgroup   =\n|akcstd     = \n|akcfss     =\n|akcmisc    =\n|ankcgroup  =\n|ankcstd    =\n|ckcgroup   =\n|ckcstd     =\n|ckcmisc    =\n|kcukgroup  = Pastoral\n|kcukstd    = http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/4728/pg_dtl_art_news/pg_hdr_art/pg_ftr_art\n|nzkcgroup  = Utility\n|nzkcstd    = http://www.nzkc.org.nz/breed_info/br638.html\n|ukcgroup   = [[Guardian Dog Group|Guardian Dog]]\n|ukcstd     = https://web.archive.org/web/20120815005026/http://www.ukcdogs.com/Web.nsf/Breeds/GuardianDog/KangalDog\n|notrecognized =\n|extinct    =\n<!-----Notes----->\n|note = KIF (Cynology Federation Of Turkey) breed standard<ref name=\"KIF\">{{cite web|title=Breed standard|url=http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/kangalbreed.pdf|format=PDF|website=Cepib.org.rs|accessdate=26 December 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Kangal Shepherd Dog''' is a breed of large [[livestock guardian dog]] in [[Sivas, Turkey]]. Originally the breed served people of Anatolia for thousands of years and continues to be a popular dog breed in Turkey. The breed is of an early [[English Mastiff|Mastiff]] type with a solid pale tan or sabled coat, and a [[melanistic mask|black mask]].  \n\nWhile the Kangal Shepherd Dog is often referred to as a [[Herding dog|sheep dog]], it is not a herding dog, but rather a flock guardian that lives with the flock of sheep to actively fend off [[predator]]s of all sizes. Typically used as protection against [[wolf|wolves]], [[bear]]s, and [[jackal]]s in its native [[Turkey]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150411064908/http://www.ukcdogs.com/Web.nsf/Breeds/KangalDog] </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-05-07/us-researchers-hope-more-assertive-foreign-dog-breeds-can-protect-livestock|title=US researchers hope more assertive, foreign dog breeds can protect livestock from wolves and bears|website=Pri.org|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> the breed has been exported to African countries like [[Namibia]] and [[Kenya]] in more recent years<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/7805813.stm|title=Guard dogs save Namibian cheetahs|date=31 December 2008|accessdate=11 December 2017|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201311160168.html|title=Namibia: Cheetah Fund Sends Kangal Dogs to Tanzania|first=|last=Waldo|date=16 November 2013|website=Allafrica.com|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> due to its intimidating size and capabilities as an effective guardian, where it successfully protects local herds from [[lion]]s, [[cheetah]]s, and similar indigenous [[big cats]], which has had the benefit of not only protecting livestock, but ensuring the continuity of [[endangered species|endangered]] predators due to reduced cullings by local farmers.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150420041920/http://newdogworld.com/kangal-dogs-save-cheetahs-from-extinction-in-africa/] </ref>\n\nThe Kangal Shepherd Dog's protectiveness, loyalty, and gentleness with small children and animals has led to its growing popularity as a guardian for families as well, as it regards people as its \"flock\" and guards them with extreme devotion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kangal.ca/breed-information/temperament/|title=Kangal Temperament|website=kangal.ca|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.petguide.com/breeds/dog/kangal-dog/|title=Kangal Dog Dog Breed Information and Pictures |website=Petguide.com|date=10 September 2014|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nThe breed's name derives from the contemporary [[Central Anatolia]]n town of [[Kangal]] in [[Turkey]]'s [[Sivas Province]], and is believed to be from the same root as the [[Turkic people|Turkic tribe]] known as the \"[[Kankalis]]\".<ref>\"[https://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kangal2&lnk=1 kangal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801052326/http://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kangal2&lnk=1 |date=1 August 2015 }}\" in ''Ni\u015fanyan S\u00f6zl\u00fck'' (Turkish Etymological Dictionary)</ref>\n\n==Appearance==\nThere are subtle variations given in the standards used by different countries when describing the height and weight. In the Kangal Shepherd Dog's homeland of Turkey, the only measurements desired are quoted by KIF as a height at the withers of {{convert|65|to|78|cm|in|abbr=on}} with a two cm tolerance either way. KIF does not differentiate between male and female statistics.\n\nThe Kangal Shepherd Dog is not as heavy as some other Mastiff breeds, allowing it greater speed and agility than larger dogs. Kangal Shepherd Dogs can reach speeds of up to 56&nbsp;km (35 miles) per hour.<ref name=\"Kangalbreed\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kangalkopegi.org/breed.html | title = The Kangal Dog of Turkey| work = | publisher = | accessdate = 2010-12-29}}</ref> \nThe under-layer provides insulation against both severe Anatolian winters and the fierce summer sun, while the outer-layer repels water and snow. This combination of coat allows it to regulate its core temperature more efficiently, while the coat is dense enough to repel rupture from wolf bites.<ref name=\"Kangalbreed\"/>\n\n\n==Temperament==\nThe Kangal Shepherd Dog is calm, controlled, independent, powerful and protective. They may be aloof towards strangers, but a well-socialized [https://www.allaboutdogs.net/kangal-dog/ Kangal Dog] is friendly with visitors and especially children. They must never be shy or vicious. A well-trained Kangal Shepherd Dog is sensitive and alert to changing situations, responding to threats with judicious warnings and courageous action if necessary. They make good guardians of livestock and humans alike, but they may not be suitable for inexperienced dog owners, as the independent intelligence of the Kangal makes for a difficult pupil.\n\n=== Protective behavior ===\n[[File:Kangal dog with spikey collar, Turkey.jpg|thumb|Kangal Shepherd Dog on duty]]\nA working Kangal Shepherd Dog on duty will station itself on a high vantage point overlooking its flock. On hot days, the dog will dig itself a hollow in the ground to keep cool. Novices learn by staying close to older dogs. The dogs will work in pairs or teams depending on the size of the flock, taking up positions around the sheep and changing their positions as needed. The intensity of their patrols around the sheep increases at nightfall.\n\nWhen suspicious, a Kangal Shepherd Dog will stand with its tail and ears erect and give an alarm call, inciting the sheep to gather around it for protection. The Kangal Shepherd Dog's first instinct is to place itself between the perceived threat and the sheep or master. Once the sheep are safely behind it, the Kangal Shepherd Dog confronts the intruder. When faced with a [[wolf]], the Kangal Shepherd Dog sometimes is successful in intimidating the enemy, but it will resort to a physical confrontation if the predator stands its ground.<ref name=\"Kangalbreed\"/> Specialized wolf killers are known as \"kurt\u00e7ul kangal\" in their homeland.\n\n\n==The Kangal Shepherd Dog internationally==\n[[File:Kangal Shepherd (livestock-guarding dog) and flock of goats in Namibia.jpg|thumb|Kangal Shepherd Dog and flock of goats in Namibia]]\nBritain's first Kangal Shepherd Dog litter was produced in 1967 by Gazi of Bakirtollo village and his mate Sabahat of Hay\u0131ro\u011flu village. Dogs from this original line formed the foundation of the so-called \"Seacop\" stock.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nIn the US, the first purebred breeding programs for Kangal Shepherd Dogs began in the early 1980s. The Kangal Shepherd Dog is recognized by the [[United Kennel Club]] in the US, and by the national kennel clubs of South Africa and New Zealand. Many Kangal Shepherd Dogs are being bred in Germany as well, mostly by immigrant workers.\n\nOn 25 June 2018, the FCI published the official Kangal Shepherd Dog breed standard to replace the previous Anatolian Shepherd Dog standard. \n\nIn [[Namibia]] the dogs are being used to help protect livestock from [[cheetah]] attacks.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/environment/article5397895.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=How mans best friend is saving endangered big cat | first=Lewis | last=Smith | date=2008-12-26 | accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> Around 500 Kangal Shepherd Dogs have been given to farmers in Namibia since 1994 by the [[Cheetah Conservation Fund]] (CCF) and the program has proved so successful that it has been extended to Kenya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheetah.org/?nd=guarding_dog_program|title=Home - Cheetah Conservation Fund : Cheetah Conservation Fund|website=Cheetah.org|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> During the past 14 years the number of cheetahs killed by farmers is calculated to have fallen from 19 per farmer annually to 2.4. Livestock losses have been cut significantly at more than 80% of the farms where the dogs have been adopted. The great majority of cheetahs that are still killed by farmers are killed after specific attacks on livestock. Previously, the cats were tracked and killed whenever they neared a farm.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Great Dane]]\n* [[Akbash dog]]\n* [[Aksaray Malaklisi dog]]\n* [[Bully Kutta]]\n* [[\u0160arplaninac]]\n* [[Anatolian Shepherd]]\n* [[Herding dog]]\n* [[Livestock guardian dog]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Kangal Dog}}\n*[http://WWW.google.com/the kangal dog breed information]\n*[http://www.kangalclub.com/ The Kangal Dog Club of America]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130611035953/http://kangalkopegi.org/ The Kangal Dog of Turkey - breed information in English]\n*[http://www.crosivka-kangal.com/ Sivas Kangalsite of Croatia/Information about history]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130503155226/http://www.anatolianworld.com/Landrace_Viewpoint.htm Viewpoint on the Anatolian, Kangal and Akbash breed debate]\n*[http://www.kangal.ca/ Kangal Dogs in Canada]\n*[http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/ Center for Preservation of Indigenous Breeds]\n* [http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/studija_kangal_eng.pdf Zootechnical analysis of two Kangal population targeted at standardization of Kangal as a Turkish dog breed]\n* [http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/kangalbreed.pdf The official breed standard of Turkish shepherd dog \u2013 Kangal] adopted by the Turkish Cynology Association, in 2011. year\n* [http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/kangal_brosura_eng.pdf Brochure about Turkish shepherd dog \u2013 Kangal]\n* [https://www.takasvolkodav.com/anatolian-shepherd-or-kangal-dog.asp? Kangal breed development in Australia]\n*[https://www.allaboutdogs.net/kangal-dog/ Kangal Dog Breed Information and Pictures]\n\n{{Livestock guardians}}\n\n[[Category:Dog breeds originating in Turkey]]\n[[Category:FCI breeds]]\n[[Category:Livestock guardian dogs]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Anatolian Shepherd Dog}}\n{{original research section|date=November 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox dog breed\n|name     = Kangal Shepherd Dog\n|image    = Varish, Berger d'anatolie, Kangal.jpeg\n|image_alt = \n|image_caption =\n|altname  = Turkish Kangal, ''Anatolian Shepherd Dog'' (old name)\n|nickname = Kangal (Anatolian, Anadolu Kangal\u0131, Karaba\u015f, Karayaka)\n|country  = Sivas, Turkey\n|patronage    = \n|coat         =\n|color        =\n|litter_size  =\n|life_span    =\n|fcigroup   = [[FCI Pinscher and Schnauzer, Molossoid and Swiss Mountain Dog Group|2]]\n|fcisection = 2.2 Molossian: Mountain type\n|fcinum     = 331\n|fcistd     = http://www.fci.be/Nomenclature/Standards/331g02-en.pdf\n|akcgroup   =\n|akcstd     = \n|akcfss     =\n|akcmisc    =\n|ankcgroup  =\n|ankcstd    =\n|ckcgroup   =\n|ckcstd     =\n|ckcmisc    =\n|kcukgroup  = Pastoral\n|kcukstd    = http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/4728/pg_dtl_art_news/pg_hdr_art/pg_ftr_art\n|nzkcgroup  = Utility\n|nzkcstd    = http://www.nzkc.org.nz/breed_info/br638.html\n|ukcgroup   = [[Guardian Dog Group|Guardian Dog]]\n|ukcstd     = https://web.archive.org/web/20120815005026/http://www.ukcdogs.com/Web.nsf/Breeds/GuardianDog/KangalDog\n|notrecognized =\n|extinct    =\n<!-----Notes----->\n|note = KIF (Cynology Federation Of Turkey) breed standard<ref name=\"KIF\">{{cite web|title=Breed standard|url=http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/kangalbreed.pdf|format=PDF|website=Cepib.org.rs|accessdate=26 December 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Kangal Shepherd Dog''' is a breed of large [[livestock guardian dog]] in [[Sivas, Turkey]]. Originally the breed served people of Anatolia for thousands of years and continues to be a popular dog breed in Turkey. The [[Anatolian Shepherd Dog]] was treated as a separate breed by many canine registries, but this is now generally treated as part of the same breed population and the Turkish Kennel Club has renamed all Anatolian Shepherds as Kangal Shepherds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Making Anatolian Shepherd Dogs into Kangal Shepherd Dogs: |url=https://www.takasvolkodav.com/page2.asp |website=Takas Volkodav |accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Kennel Club\"/><ref name=\"Dog World\"/><ref name=Oz/><ref name=FCI/> The breed is of an early [[English Mastiff|Mastiff]] type with a solid pale tan or sabled coat, and a [[melanistic mask|black mask]].  According to official Kangal Shepherd Dog organisations in Turkey, including the Cynology Federation of Turkey (K\u00f6pek Irklar\u0131 ve Kinoloji Federasyonu, KIF) and the Ankara Kangal Association (Ankara Kangal Derne\u011fi, ANKADER), Kangals may also be brindle<ref name=\"KIF\"/> or feature a recessive black tan pattern;<ref>{{cite web|last=Isik|first=Guvener|title=Dogan Kartay Interview|url=http://www.anatoliandog.org/isik-005.htm|date=2006|website=Anatoliandog.org|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> with or without a black mask; and/or with white markings.\n\nWhile the Kangal Shepherd Dog is often referred to as a [[Herding dog|sheep dog]], it is not a herding dog, but rather a flock guardian that lives with the flock of sheep to actively fend off [[predator]]s of all sizes. Typically used as protection against [[wolf|wolves]], [[bear]]s, and [[jackal]]s in its native [[Turkey]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150411064908/http://www.ukcdogs.com/Web.nsf/Breeds/KangalDog] </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-05-07/us-researchers-hope-more-assertive-foreign-dog-breeds-can-protect-livestock|title=US researchers hope more assertive, foreign dog breeds can protect livestock from wolves and bears|website=Pri.org|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> the breed has been exported to African countries like [[Namibia]] and [[Kenya]] in more recent years<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/7805813.stm|title=Guard dogs save Namibian cheetahs|date=31 December 2008|accessdate=11 December 2017|website=News.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201311160168.html|title=Namibia: Cheetah Fund Sends Kangal Dogs to Tanzania|first=|last=Waldo|date=16 November 2013|website=Allafrica.com|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> due to its intimidating size and capabilities as an effective guardian, where it successfully protects local herds from [[lion]]s, [[cheetah]]s, and similar indigenous [[big cats]], which has had the benefit of not only protecting livestock, but ensuring the continuity of [[endangered species|endangered]] predators due to reduced cullings by local farmers.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150420041920/http://newdogworld.com/kangal-dogs-save-cheetahs-from-extinction-in-africa/] </ref>\n\nThe Kangal Shepherd Dog's protectiveness, loyalty, and gentleness with small children and animals has led to its growing popularity as a guardian for families as well, as it regards people as its \"flock\" and guards them with extreme devotion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kangal.ca/breed-information/temperament/|title=Kangal Temperament|website=kangal.ca|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.petguide.com/breeds/dog/kangal-dog/|title=Kangal Dog Dog Breed Information and Pictures |website=Petguide.com|date=10 September 2014|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\nThe breed's name derives from the contemporary [[Central Anatolia]]n town of [[Kangal]] in [[Turkey]]'s [[Sivas Province]], and is believed to be from the same root as the [[Turkic people|Turkic tribe]] known as the \"[[Kankalis]]\".<ref>\"[https://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kangal2&lnk=1 kangal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801052326/http://www.nisanyansozluk.com/?k=kangal2&lnk=1 |date=1 August 2015 }}\" in ''Ni\u015fanyan S\u00f6zl\u00fck'' (Turkish Etymological Dictionary)</ref>\n\n==Appearance==\nThere are subtle variations given in the standards used by different countries when describing the height and weight. In the Kangal Shepherd Dog's homeland of Turkey, the only measurements desired are quoted by KIF as a height at the withers of {{convert|65|to|78|cm|in|abbr=on}} with a two cm tolerance either way. KIF does not differentiate between male and female statistics.<ref name=\"KIF\"/> Although other standards internationally are fairly consistent with each other, they are at odds with KIF as their guidelines are for a larger dog. In the UK, the Kennel Club interim standard states the height at shoulders should be males {{convert|74|to|81|cm|in|abbr=on}} with females at {{convert|71|to|79|cm|in|abbr=on}} without specifying any weight guidelines.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interim standard, Turkish Kangal Dog|url=http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/4728/pg_dtl_art_news/pg_hdr_art/pg_ftr_art|publisher=Kennel Club (UK)|accessdate=19 January 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130423200831/http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/4728/pg_dtl_art_news/pg_hdr_art/pg_ftr_art|archive-date=23 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The New Zealand Kennel Club quotes height for males as {{convert|76|to|81.5|cm|in|abbr=on}} with a weight of {{convert|50|to|63|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and a females height as {{convert|71|to|78.5|cm|in|abbr=on}} weighing {{convert|41|to|59|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breed standard|url=http://www.nzkc.org.nz/breed_info/br638.html|publisher=New Zealand KC|accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref> In America, the only agency to recognise the breed is the UKC and its standard gives {{convert|30|to|32|in|cm|abbr=on}} for males, weight {{convert|110|to|145|lb|kg|abbr=on}} and {{convert|28|to|30|in|cm|abbr=on}} for females with a weight of {{convert|90|to|120|lb|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breed standard|url=http://www.ukcdogs.com/Web.nsf/Breeds/GuardianDog/KangalDog|publisher=United Kennel Club|accessdate=2010-04-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815005026/http://www.ukcdogs.com/Web.nsf/Breeds/GuardianDog/KangalDog|archivedate=2012-08-15}}</ref>\n\nThe Kangal Shepherd Dog is not as heavy as some other Mastiff breeds, allowing it greater speed and agility than larger dogs. Kangal Shepherd Dogs can reach speeds of up to 56&nbsp;km (35 miles) per hour.<ref name=\"Kangalbreed\">{{cite web | url = http://www.kangalkopegi.org/breed.html | title = The Kangal Dog of Turkey| work = | publisher = | accessdate = 2010-12-29}}</ref> \nThe under-layer provides insulation against both severe Anatolian winters and the fierce summer sun, while the outer-layer repels water and snow. This combination of coat allows it to regulate its core temperature more efficiently, while the coat is dense enough to repel rupture from wolf bites.<ref name=\"Kangalbreed\"/>\nFurther differences between the KIF standard and those used internationally are found in the guidelines for coat and colour. The registered Kangal Shepherd Dog organizations in Turkey, Cynology Federation Of Turkey (KIF)\u2014to an extent\u2014and Ankara Kangal Derne\u011fi (ANKADER) do not regard coat colour as a breed defining feature. Brindle, recessive black tan pattern, white markings and a longer coat are regarded as Kangal and are not usually indicative of cross breeding, as the KIF standard as significant restrictions on accepted color and is more restrictive with respect to white markings than any of the other international standards, as white markings are only accepted on the chest and on the tip of the tail, whereas standards from other kennel clubs allow white markings on the feet and legs. Rather it is head structure and morphology that differentiate Kangal from other \u00c7oban K\u00f6pegi.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn contrast other kennel clubs describe coat and colour as perhaps the most visible traits that distinguish the Kangal from the [[Akbash dog|Akbash]] and [[Anatolian Shepherd Dog|Anatolian]]. The coat must be short and dense, not long or feathery, and of a pale fawn or tan color with varying amounts of sable guard hairs. All Kangal Shepherd Dogs have a [[Melanistic mask|black facial mask]], and black or shaded ears. White at certain points (chest, chin, toes) may or may not be allowed, depending on the standard. Some heavily sabled Kangals also have darker legs and chests. Most importantly, the coat should not be broken, [[brindle]]d, or spotted. Cropping of the ears is done for several reasons, including the cultural demonstration of ownership vice feral dog, for appearance and for protection, as long ears can be vulnerable in a physical confrontation with a predator.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} The cropping of ears is illegal in the UK.\n<gallery>\nFile:TurkishKangal.jpg|A Kangal with cropped ears\nFile:Kangal dog puppy eating yoghurt.jpg|Kangal dog puppy eating yogurt\nFile:Kangal-welpen-de 010.jpg|The Kangal dog can be a good house dog if effectively trained from birth\nFile:Cobra-BlackMamba 2.jpg\nKral jrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrr.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==Temperament==\nThe Kangal Shepherd Dog is calm, controlled, independent, powerful and protective. They may be aloof towards strangers, but a well-socialized [https://www.allaboutdogs.net/kangal-dog/ Kangal Dog] is friendly with visitors and especially children. They must never be shy or vicious. A well-trained Kangal Shepherd Dog is sensitive and alert to changing situations, responding to threats with judicious warnings and courageous action if necessary. They make good guardians of livestock and humans alike, but they may not be suitable for inexperienced dog owners, as the independent intelligence of the Kangal makes for a difficult pupil.\n\n=== Protective behavior ===\n[[File:Kangal dog with spikey collar, Turkey.jpg|thumb|Kangal Shepherd Dog on duty]]\nA working Kangal Shepherd Dog on duty will station itself on a high vantage point overlooking its flock. On hot days, the dog will dig itself a hollow in the ground to keep cool. Novices learn by staying close to older dogs. The dogs will work in pairs or teams depending on the size of the flock, taking up positions around the sheep and changing their positions as needed. The intensity of their patrols around the sheep increases at nightfall.\n\nWhen suspicious, a Kangal Shepherd Dog will stand with its tail and ears erect and give an alarm call, inciting the sheep to gather around it for protection. The Kangal Shepherd Dog's first instinct is to place itself between the perceived threat and the sheep or master. Once the sheep are safely behind it, the Kangal Shepherd Dog confronts the intruder. When faced with a [[wolf]], the Kangal Shepherd Dog sometimes is successful in intimidating the enemy, but it will resort to a physical confrontation if the predator stands its ground.<ref name=\"Kangalbreed\"/> Specialized wolf killers are known as \"kurt\u00e7ul kangal\" in their homeland.\n\n== Kangal/Anatolian Shepherd ==\nThe UK Kennel Club announced it will recognise the Kangal Shepherd Dog as a breed with effect from July 2013. It also stated that dogs currently registered as Anatolian Shepherd Dogs may be eligible (where appropriate) to be recorded as Turkish Kangal Dogs instead.<ref name=\"Kennel Club\">{{cite web|title=Recognition of the Turkish Kangal dog |url=http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/4581/23/5/3 |publisher=Kennel Club |accessdate=4 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011003633/http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/4581/23/5/3 |archivedate=11 October 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"Dog World\">{{cite web|title=KC to recognise the Turkish Kangal Dog|url=http://www.dogworld.co.uk/product.php/80650|publisher=Dog World|accessdate=4 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001909/http://www.dogworld.co.uk/product.php/80650|archivedate=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of 1 January 2012, the Australian National Kennel Council no longer recognises the ANKC Kangal as being a separate breed from the ANKC Anatolian Shepherd.<ref name=Oz>{{cite web|url=http://ankc.org.au/News.aspx?id=408|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125004152/http://ankc.org.au/News.aspx?id=408|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 January 2013|title=Australian National Kennel Council|date=25 January 2013|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n15 June 2018 the FCI effected the one breed population model enacted by the ANKC in 2012, and approved the breed name change of Standard No. 331 Anatolian Shepherd Dog to Kangal Shepherd Dog.  The breed population of FCI Kangal Shepherd Dogs is the same breed population as FCI Anatolian Shepherd Dog.  All FCI Anatolian Shepherd Dogs now have the breed name of: Kangal Shepherd Dog. <ref name=FCI>[http://www.fci.be/en/nomenclature/KANGAL-SHEPHERD-DOG-331.html FCI: Kangal Shepherd Dog.]</ref>\n\n==The Kangal Shepherd Dog internationally==\n[[File:Kangal Shepherd (livestock-guarding dog) and flock of goats in Namibia.jpg|thumb|Kangal Shepherd Dog and flock of goats in Namibia]]\nBritain's first Kangal Shepherd Dog litter was produced in 1967 by Gazi of Bakirtollo village and his mate Sabahat of Hay\u0131ro\u011flu village. Dogs from this original line formed the foundation of the so-called \"Seacop\" stock.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nIn October 2012 [[The Kennel Club]] announced it will recognise the Kangal Shepherd Dog as a breed and classify it within the [[Pastoral Group]]. This will allow the breed to be exhibited at KC licensed events in the UK from July 2013.<ref name=\"Dog World\"/> In December 2012 an interim [[Breed standard (dogs)|Breed standard]] for the breed will be issued.<ref name=\"Kennel Club\"/> The interim standard was issued in January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Turkish Kangal Dog; proposed interim standard|url=http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/4728/pg_dtl_art_news/pg_hdr_art/pg_ftr_art|publisher=The Kennel Club|accessdate=19 January 2013|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130423200831/http://www.thekennelclub.org.uk/item/4728/pg_dtl_art_news/pg_hdr_art/pg_ftr_art|archive-date=23 April 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the US, the first purebred breeding programs for Kangal Shepherd Dogs began in the early 1980s. The Kangal Shepherd Dog is recognized by the [[United Kennel Club]] in the US, and by the national kennel clubs of South Africa and New Zealand. Many Kangal Shepherd Dogs are being bred in Germany as well, mostly by immigrant workers. Some are registered as Anatolians, that being the only registration option open to them in Germany; most are unregistered.\n\nOn January 1, 2012, the Australian National Kennel Club discontinued its recognition of the ANKC Kangal Dog as a separate breed to the Anatolian Shepherd Dog.<ref>{{cite web|title=ANKC |url=http://www.ankc.org.au/News.aspx?id=408 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116031652/http://ankc.org.au/News.aspx?id=408 |archivedate=2012-11-16 }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June 2018, the FCI published the official Kangal Shepherd Dog breed standard to replace the previous Anatolian Shepherd Dog standard. \n\nIn [[Namibia]] the dogs are being used to help protect livestock from [[cheetah]] attacks.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/environment/article5397895.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=How mans best friend is saving endangered big cat | first=Lewis | last=Smith | date=2008-12-26 | accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> Around 500 Kangal Shepherd Dogs have been given to farmers in Namibia since 1994 by the [[Cheetah Conservation Fund]] (CCF) and the program has proved so successful that it has been extended to Kenya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheetah.org/?nd=guarding_dog_program|title=Home - Cheetah Conservation Fund : Cheetah Conservation Fund|website=Cheetah.org|accessdate=11 December 2017}}</ref> During the past 14 years the number of cheetahs killed by farmers is calculated to have fallen from 19 per farmer annually to 2.4. Livestock losses have been cut significantly at more than 80% of the farms where the dogs have been adopted. The great majority of cheetahs that are still killed by farmers are killed after specific attacks on livestock. Previously, the cats were tracked and killed whenever they neared a farm.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Great Dane]]\n* [[Akbash dog]]\n* [[Aksaray Malaklisi dog]]\n* [[Bully Kutta]]\n* [[\u0160arplaninac]]\n* [[Anatolian Shepherd]]\n* [[Herding dog]]\n* [[Livestock guardian dog]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Kangal Dog}}\n*[http://WWW.google.com/the kangal dog breed information]\n*[http://www.kangalclub.com/ The Kangal Dog Club of America]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130611035953/http://kangalkopegi.org/ The Kangal Dog of Turkey - breed information in English]\n*[http://www.crosivka-kangal.com/ Sivas Kangalsite of Croatia/Information about history]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130503155226/http://www.anatolianworld.com/Landrace_Viewpoint.htm Viewpoint on the Anatolian, Kangal and Akbash breed debate]\n*[http://www.kangal.ca/ Kangal Dogs in Canada]\n*[http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/ Center for Preservation of Indigenous Breeds]\n* [http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/studija_kangal_eng.pdf Zootechnical analysis of two Kangal population targeted at standardization of Kangal as a Turkish dog breed]\n* [http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/kangalbreed.pdf The official breed standard of Turkish shepherd dog \u2013 Kangal] adopted by the Turkish Cynology Association, in 2011. year\n* [http://www.cepib.org.rs/wp-en/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/kangal_brosura_eng.pdf Brochure about Turkish shepherd dog \u2013 Kangal]\n* [https://www.takasvolkodav.com/anatolian-shepherd-or-kangal-dog.asp? Kangal breed development in Australia]\n*[https://www.allaboutdogs.net/kangal-dog/ Kangal Dog Breed Information and Pictures]\n\n{{Livestock guardians}}\n\n[[Category:Dog breeds originating in Turkey]]\n[[Category:FCI breeds]]\n[[Category:Livestock guardian dogs]]\n", "name_user": "Lloydchristmasharry", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I have deleted major misinformation.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kangal_Shepherd_Dog"}
{"title_page": "Muhammad al-Riquti", "text_new": "{{short description|Muslim scholar and physician}}\n'''Abu Bakr Muhammad ibn Ahmad al-Riquti al-Mursi'''{{sfn|Sams\u00f3|1981|p=173}} (\u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0628\u0643\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0642\u0648\u0637\u064a,  also spelled '''Abubequer Mohamed ibn Ahmed Al-Ricot\u00ed''') was a thirteenth-century Muslim scholar and physician from [[Murcia]]. He founded and led a school where he taught Muslims, Christians, and Jews, under the patronage of [[Alfonso X of Castile|Alfonso the Wise]]. Later, he migrated to the [[Emirate of Granada]] at the invitation of Sultan [[Muhammad II of Granada|Muhammad II]].\n\n== Biography ==\nAl-Riquti was from the city of [[Murcia]] (hence his [[Nisba (onomastics)|nisba]] ''al-Mursi''), and according to historian [[Ibn al-Khatib]] (1313\u20131375) he was an expert in logic, mathematics, arithmetic, music, and medicine.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}} He spoke Arabic and the local [[Romance languages|Romance language]], and possibly Latin and Hebrew as well.{{sfn|Sams\u00f3|1981|p=175}} Murcia was formerly the seat of [[Taifa of Murcia|small Muslim kingdom]] and also an intellectual center,<ref name=uni>{{cite web|url=https://www.um.es/estructura/internacional/in/institucional/historia/precendentes.php|title=Medieval Precedents|publisher=Universidad de Murcia|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> which was conquered by [[Crown of Castile|Castile]] in 1243 and became a semi-independent protectorate. The Castilian prince Alfonso (the future [[Alfonso X of Castile]]) allowed al-Riquti to found a school and teach Muslims, Christians, and Jews alike.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}} Ibn al-Khatib wrote that al-Riquti taught the three religious groups \"in their own languages\", and described this school as a \"[[madrasa]]\". Several modern historians hypothesize that it might be the [[Studia Linguarum]] of the [[Dominican Order|Dominicans]] in Murcia.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|pp=50\u201351}} The modern [[University of Murcia]] considered this school as one of the university's forerunners.<ref name=uni/> While most historians assume that al-Riquti's school was located in Murcia, the historian [[Gerard Albert Wiegers]] instead identifies it with a ''Estudio general'' built by Alfonso in [[Seville]] in 1254.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|pp=50\u201352}} \n\nAlfonso X became king in 1252 and adopted the policy of encouraging Muslim scholars to stay in conquered formerly Muslim territories and offering rewards for those who converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Vernet|Sams\u00f3|1996|p=271}} Meanwhile, Muslims in Murcia [[Mud\u00e9jar revolt of 1264\u20131266|rebelled in 1264]], and after it was [[Conquest of Murcia (1265\u201366)|defeated by the royal forces]] in 1266 the region lost its autonomy.<ref name=uni/> Many Muslim intellectuals lost their privileges; al-Riquti felt anxious about the situation and about Alfonso's encouragement to convert to Christianity.<ref name=uni/>{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}} Meanwhile, in 1273 [[Muhammad II of Granada|Muhammad II]] became the [[Emirate of Granada|Sultan of Granada]], the last Muslim state of Spain. He was known as al-Faqih (\"the canon lawyer\") and competed with Alfonso in attracting learned men to his emirate.{{sfn|Vernet|Sams\u00f3|1996|p=272}} Al-Riquti migrated to Granada at the Sultan's instigation.{{sfn|Vernet|Sams\u00f3|1996|p=271}}{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}} In Granada he was involved in a number of debates, and he held a respectable position until he died.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}}{{sfn|Urvoy|1992|p=874}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv|first=Julio|last=Sams\u00f3|authorlink=Julio Sams\u00f3|title=Dos colaboradores cient\u00edficos musulmanes de Alfonso X|journal=Llull: Revista de la Sociedad Espa\u00f1ola de Historia de las Ciencias y de las T\u00e9cnicas|issn=0210-8615|volume=4|issue=6\u20137|year=1981|pages=171\u2013180|url=https://dialnet.unirioja.es/descarga/articulo/61993.pdf}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv|first1=Dominique|last1=Urvoy|authorlink1=Dominique Urvoy |title=The Ulama of al-Andalus |pages=849\u2013877|editors=Salma Khadra Jayyusi, Manuela Mar\u00edn|encyclopedia=The Legacy of Muslim Spain | date=1992|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-09599-3}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv|first1=Juan|last1=Vernet|authorlink1=Juan Vernet|first2=Julio|last2=Sams\u00f3|title=The development of Arabic science in Andalusia |pages=243\u2013275|editor=[[Roshdi Rashed]]|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of the History of Arabic Science | date=1996|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-12410-2|oclc=912501823}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wiegers|first=Gerard|title=Islamic Literature in Spanish and Aljamiado: Y\u00e7a of Segovia (fl. 1450), His Antecendents and Successors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z2A55_kw3F4C|year=1994|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-09936-0|ref=harv}}\n\n\n[[Category:People of the Emirate of Granada]]\n[[Category:People from Murcia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Muslim scholar and physician}}\n'''Abu Bakr Muhammad ibn Ahmad al-Riquti al-Mursi'''{{sfn|Sams\u00f3|1981|p=173}} (\u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0628\u0643\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0623\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0642\u0648\u0637\u064a,  also spelled '''Abubequer Mohamed ibn Ahmed Al-Ricot\u00ed''') was a thirteenth-century Muslim scholar and physician from [[Murcia]]. He founded and led a school where he taught Muslims, Christians, and Jews, under the patronage of [[Alfonso X of Castile|Alfonso the Wise]]. Later, he migrated to the [[Emirate of Granada]] at the invitation of Sultan [[Muhammad II of Granada|Muhammad II]].\n\n== Biography ==\nAl-Riquti was from the city of [[Murcia]] (hence his [[Nisba (onomastics)|nisba]] ''al-Mursi''), and according to historian [[Ibn al-Khatib]] (1313\u20131375) he was an expert in logic, mathematics, arithmetic, music, and medicine.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}} He spoke Arabic and the local [[Romance languages|Romance language]], and possibly Latin and Hebrew as well.{{sfn|Sams\u00f3|1981|p=175}} Murcia was formerly the seat of [[Taifa of Murcia|small Muslim kingdom]] and also an intellectual center,<ref name=uni>{{cite web|url=https://www.um.es/estructura/internacional/in/institucional/historia/precendentes.php|title=Medieval Precedents|publisher=Universidad de Murcia|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> which was conquered by [[Crown of Castile|Castile]] in 1243 and became a semi-independent protectorate. The Castilian prince Alfonso (the future [[Alfonso X of Castile]]) allowed al-Riquti to found a school and taught Muslims, Christians, and Jews alike.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}} Ibn al-Khatib wrote that al-Riquti taught the three religious groups \"in their own languages\", and described this school as a \"[[madrasa]]\". Several modern historians hypothesize that it might be the [[Studia Linguarum]] of the [[Dominican Order|Dominicans]] in Murcia.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|pp=50\u201351}} The modern [[University of Murcia]] considered this school as one of the university's forerunners.<ref name=uni/> While most historians assume that al-Riquti's school was located in Murcia, the historian [[Gerard Albert Wiegers]] instead identifies it with a ''Estudio general'' built by Alfonso in [[Seville]] in 1254.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|pp=50\u201352}} \n\nAlfonso X became king in 1252 and adopted the policy of encouraging Muslim scholars to stay in conquered formerly Muslim territories and offering rewards for those who converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Vernet|Sams\u00f3|1996|p=271}} Meanwhile, Muslims in Murcia [[Mud\u00e9jar revolt of 1264\u20131266|rebelled in 1264]], and after it was [[Conquest of Murcia (1265\u201366)|defeated by the royal forces]] in 1266 the region lost its autonomy.<ref name=uni/> Many Muslim intellectuals lost their privileges; al-Riquti felt anxious about the situation and about Alfonso's encouragement to convert to Christianity.<ref name=uni/>{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}} Meanwhile, in 1273 [[Muhammad II of Granada|Muhammad II]] became the [[Emirate of Granada|Sultan of Granada]], the last Muslim state of Spain. He was known as al-Faqih (\"the canon lawyer\") and competed with Alfonso in attracting learned men to his emirate.{{sfn|Vernet|Sams\u00f3|1996|p=272}} Al-Riquti migrated to Granada at the Sultan's instigation.{{sfn|Vernet|Sams\u00f3|1996|p=271}}{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}} In Granada he was involved in a number of debates, and he held a respectable position until he died.{{sfn|Wiegers|1994|p=50}}{{sfn|Urvoy|1992|p=874}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite journal|ref=harv|first=Julio|last=Sams\u00f3|authorlink=Julio Sams\u00f3|title=Dos colaboradores cient\u00edficos musulmanes de Alfonso X|journal=Llull: Revista de la Sociedad Espa\u00f1ola de Historia de las Ciencias y de las T\u00e9cnicas|issn=0210-8615|volume=4|issue=6\u20137|year=1981|pages=171\u2013180|url=https://dialnet.unirioja.es/descarga/articulo/61993.pdf}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv|first1=Dominique|last1=Urvoy|authorlink1=Dominique Urvoy |title=The Ulama of al-Andalus |pages=849\u2013877|editors=Salma Khadra Jayyusi, Manuela Mar\u00edn|encyclopedia=The Legacy of Muslim Spain | date=1992|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-09599-3}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|ref=harv|first1=Juan|last1=Vernet|authorlink1=Juan Vernet|first2=Julio|last2=Sams\u00f3|title=The development of Arabic science in Andalusia |pages=243\u2013275|editor=[[Roshdi Rashed]]|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of the History of Arabic Science | date=1996|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-12410-2|oclc=912501823}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wiegers|first=Gerard|title=Islamic Literature in Spanish and Aljamiado: Y\u00e7a of Segovia (fl. 1450), His Antecendents and Successors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z2A55_kw3F4C|year=1994|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-09936-0|ref=harv}}\n\n\n[[Category:People of the Emirate of Granada]]\n[[Category:People from Murcia]]\n", "name_user": "Yoninah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muhammad_al-Riquti"}
{"title_page": "Destin Daniel Cretton", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Destin Daniel Cretton\n| image       = Destin Daniel Cretton by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption     = Cretton at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name   = <!--- Only included if birth name differs from article name --->\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1978|11|23}}\n| birth_place  = [[Haiku, Hawaii]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Featured Filmmaker: Destin Cretton, Writer/Director of 'Short Term 12\u2032|url=http://news.mauifilmfestival.net/2013/06/17/destin-cretton-short-term-12/|work=Maui Film Festival|accessdate=July 9, 2014|date=June 17, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113222801/http://news.mauifilmfestival.net/2013/06/17/destin-cretton-short-term-12/|archivedate=2017-11-13|url-status=dead|last=Tekula|first=Sara}}</ref>\n| alma_mater = [[Point Loma Nazarene University]]<br />[[San Diego State University]]\n| occupation  = Film director, screenwriter, producer, editor\n| years_active = 2002\u2013present\n| spouse(s) = Nikki Chapman\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Destin Daniel Cretton''' (born November 23, 1978)<ref>{{cite web|title=United States Public Records Index|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/2S5M-3ZY|work=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> is an American film director, screenwriter, producer, and editor. He is best known for his collaborations with [[Brie Larson]], in the films ''[[Short Term 12]]'' (2013), ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]]'' (2017), and ''[[Just Mercy]]'' (2019).\n\n== Early life ==\nCretton was born in 1978 in [[Haiku, Hawaii]] on the island of [[Maui]], the son of Janice Harue Cretton, a [[Japanese American]] hairdresser, and Daniel Cretton, of [[Irish American|Irish]] and [[Slovak American|Slovak]] ancestry, who worked for the fire department.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/alisonwillmore/28-asian-american-filmakers|title=28 Asian-American Filmmakers You Need To Know|first=Alison|last=Willmore|website=BuzzFeed|date=May 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nichibei.org/2018/01/the-great-unknown-and-the-unknown-great-cinematic-20th-century-nikkei/|title=THE GREAT UNKNOWN AND THE UNKNOWN GREAT: Cinematic 20th century Nikkei \u00bb Nichi Bei|website=www.nichibei.org|date=January 1, 2018|last=Robinson|first=Greg }}</ref> He was home-schooled by his Christian mother.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://hanahou.com/16.5/moving-pictures|title=Moving Pictures|website=Hana Hou!|issue=16.5|last=Wianecki|first=Shannon|date=October\u2013November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mauinews.com/news/local-news/2017/08/filmmaker-recalls-his-haiku-past-while-directing-the-glass-castle/|title=Filmmaker recalls his Haiku past while directing \u2018The Glass Castle\u2019|website=The Maui News|publisher=|last=Sugidono|first=Chris|date=August 11, 2017}}</ref> He lived in Haiku in a two-bedroom house with his five siblings,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Valentini |first1=Valentina |title=Director Destin Daniel Cretton Has Always Lived in The Glass Castle |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/08/the-glass-castle-destin-daniel-cretton-brie-larson-jeannette-walls-short-term-12 |work=Vanity Fair |date=August 8, 2017}}</ref> including sister Joy, until he was 19 years old. He moved to [[San Diego]], [[California]] to attend [[Point Loma Nazarene University]], where he majored in [[communications]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldstein|first=Jessica|title='Short Term 12' writer-director Destin Daniel Cretton on real-life inspiration behind his film|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/short-term-12-writer-director-destin-daniel-cretton-on-real-life-inspiration-behind-his-film/2013/08/28/e0025ebc-0e6e-11e3-bdf6-e4fc677d94a1_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=February 5, 2014|date=August 30, 2013}}</ref> After graduating, Cretton worked for two years as a staff person at a group home for at-risk teenagers.<ref name=\"IW\">{{cite web|title=Meet the 2013 SXSW Filmmakers #30: 'Hipster' Destin Daniel Cretton Returns With Brie Larson Starring Drama 'Short Term 12'|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/meet-the-2013-sxsw-filmmakers-52|work=[[Indiewire]]|accessdate=February 5, 2014|date=March 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Adams|first=Sam|title=Short Term 12 filmmaker Destin Cretton|url=http://thedissolve.com/features/emerging/105-destin-cretton/|work=The Dissolve|accessdate=February 5, 2014|date=August 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe made short films as a hobby, which developed as a vocational path. He attended and graduated from film school at [[San Diego State University]].<ref name=\"IW\" />\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Destin Daniel Cretton cropped.jpg|thumb|Cretton at the [[Deauville American Film Festival]] in 2013|alt=|left|207x207px]]\nWhile at San Diego State University, Cretton made a 22-minute short film, ''Short Term 12'', based on his experiences at the facility for teenagers. The short film premiered at the [[2009 Sundance Film Festival]], where it won the Jury Prize in Short Filmmaking.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/short-term-12-writer-director-destin-daniel-cretton-on-real-life-inspiration-behind-his-film/2013/08/28/e0025ebc-0e6e-11e3-bdf6-e4fc677d94a1_story.html|title=\u2018Short Term 12\u2019 writer-director Destin Daniel Cretton on real-life inspiration behind his film|last=Goldstein|first=Jessica|date=August 31, 2013|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from film school, Cretton decided to adapt the short into a feature-length screenplay, which won one of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]' five [[Nicholl Fellowships in Screenwriting]] in 2010.<ref name=\"viva\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.vivaverve.com/shopimages/documents/ST12%20Production%20Notes.pdf|title=Short Term 12|publisher=Verve Pictures|year=2013|accessdate=April 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThat screenplay served as the basis for what would become the [[Short Term 12|feature film of the same name]], also directed by Cretton, which was released in 2013.<ref name=\"SDCB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sdcitybeat.com/sandiego/article-12161-the-rise-of-destin-daniel-cretton.html|title=The rise of Destin Daniel Cretton|last=Bradford|first=Ryan|date=September 4, 2013|work=San Diego City Beat|publisher=[[Southland Publishing]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222135924/http://www.sdcitybeat.com/sandiego/article-12161-the-rise-of-destin-daniel-cretton.html|archive-date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> The film premiered on March 10, 2013 at [[South by Southwest]], where it won the Grand Jury and Audience Awards for a Narrative Feature.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/global/memento-rolls-out-short-term-12-exclusive-1200576825/|title=Memento Rolls Out \u2018Short Term 12\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Hopewell|first=John|date=August 11, 2013|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014}}</ref> Widely acclaimed as one of the best films of 2013, it was listed on many film critics' annual top ten lists.<ref name=\"acclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critic-top-10-lists-best-movies-of-2013|title=Film Critic Top 10 Lists - Best Movies of 2013|work=Metacritic|accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref> The film earned several accolades, including three [[Independent Spirit Award]] nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/03/01/indie-spirit-awards-2014-winners-list/|title=Independent Spirit Awards 2014: The winners list|last=Atkinson|first=Katie|date=March 1, 2014|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Cretton was attached to rewrite the script and direct ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]]'', an adaptation of [[Jeannette Walls]]' [[The Glass Castle|2005 best-selling memoir of the same name]] about a successful young woman raised by severely dysfunctional parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/jennifer-lawrences-glass-castle-gains-momentum-at-lionsgate-1201278534/|title = Jennifer Lawrence's 'Glass Castle' Gains Momentum at Lionsgate|last = McNary|first = Dave|website = Variety|language = en-US|date=August 8, 2014|access-date = 2016-03-26}}</ref> Starring Larson, the film also features [[Woody Harrelson]] and [[Naomi Watts]] as her alcoholic father and eccentric mother, respectively.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/naomi-watts-talks-join-brie-878672|title=Naomi Watts in Talks to Join Brie Larson in Drama 'Glass Castle' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=2016-03-29|access-date=2016-03-30}}</ref> Larson's role was originally considered by [[Jennifer Lawrence]], but she dropped out while the studio was seeking the male lead.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://deadline.com/2015/11/woody-harrelson-the-glass-castle-opposite-brie-larson-1201609016/|title = Woody Harrelson in Talks For 'The Glass Castle' Opposite Brie Larson|last = Busch|first = Anita|website = Deadline|language = en-US|date=November 5, 2015|access-date = 2016-03-26}}</ref> The film was released on August 10, 2017.<ref name=\":0\" /> It received mixed reviews from critics; they praised the performances of its cast (particularly Larson and Harrelson) but criticized the emotional tones and adaptation of the source material.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/annabelle-creation-is-a-potent-prequel/|title=Annabelle: Creation is a Potent Prequel|last=Giles|first=Jeff|date=August 10, 2017|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, it was announced that [[Ryan Coogler]] had teamed up with Cretton and poet/playwright [[Chinaka Hodge]] to develop ''Minors'', a new television drama series produced by Charles D. King. Drawing from Cretton's experiences working in residential foster care, Hodge's background teaching under-served youth in San Francisco Bay area continuation schools, and Coogler's upbringing in the East Bay, ''Minors'' promises to take an unflinching look at institutionalization, exploring juvenile facilities and the children who grow up in that system. The series will show how that system shapes young people over a one-year period. Hodge will write the series, and Coogler and Cretton will direct.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://deadline.com/2016/02/creed-director-ryan-coogler-developing-series-drama-minors-1201709611/|title = Ryan Coogler Teams With Destin Daniel Cretton & Chinaka Hodge For TV Drama 'Minors'|last = Lincoln|first = Ross A.|website = Deadline|language = en-US|date=February 25, 2016|access-date = 2016-03-25}}</ref>\n\nCretton subsequently teamed with Larson and [[Michael B. Jordan]] for ''[[Just Mercy]]'', a drama film based on civil rights defense attorney [[Bryan Stevenson]]'s ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' bestselling memoir: ''Just Mercy: A Story of Justice and Redemption.''<ref name=\"Deadline Marvel\">{{Cite web|url = https://deadline.com/2019/03/destin-creston-shang-chi-marvel-choice-1202575136/|title = Destin Daniel Cretton Marvel\u2019s Choice To Direct \u2018Shang-Chi\u2019|website = Deadline|last=Fleming Jr.|first=Mike|date=March 13, 2019|language = en-US|access-date = 2019-04-19}}</ref> Stevenson founded the Equal Justice Institute in Montgomery, Alabama, where he provided defense counsel to men on death row. The plot follows Stevenson (Jordan) as he explores the case of a death row prisoner, [[Walter McMillian]], whom he fought to free.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://deadline.com/2018/08/brie-larson-michael-b-jordan-just-mercy-destin-cretton-warner-bros-1202442881/|title = Brie Larson In Talks To Join Michael B. Jordan In \u2018Just Mercy\u2019|author=Denise Petski, Dino-Ray Ramos|date=August 8, 2018|website = Deadline|language = en-US|access-date = 2019-04-19}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 6, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/|title=Toronto Film Festival: 'Joker,' 'Ford v Ferrari,' 'Hustlers' Among Big Premieres|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=July 23, 2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref> and was theatrically released on December 25, 2019, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]. ''Just Mercy'' was critically acclaimed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-b-jordans-just-mercy-lands-year-end-awards-release-sesame-street-pushed-1224638|title=Michael B. Jordan's 'Just Mercy' Lands Year-End Awards Release; 'Sesame Street' Officially Pushed|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Cretton was hired by [[Marvel Studios]] to direct a film based on [[Shang-Chi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-sets-director-destin-daniel-cretton-1194443|title=Marvel's 'Shang-Chi' Sets Director Destin Daniel Cretton|website=Hollywood Reporter|first1=Borys |last1=Kit|first2=Aaron |last2=Couch|date=March 13, 2019|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}</ref> Both the film and Cretton's involvement were confirmed during the [[San Diego Comic-Con]] 2019, with the film being titled ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]''.<ref name=\"Shang-ChiComic-Con\">{{cite web|url= https://variety.com/2019/film/news/simu-liu-marvels-shang-chi-1203268497/|first= Justin|last= Kroll|title= Marvel's ''Shang-Chi'' Finds Its Lead|work= Variety|date= July 20, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190721174008/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/simu-liu-marvels-shang-chi-1203268497/|archivedate= July 21, 2019|url-status= live|df= mdy-all|access-date= July 20, 2019}}</ref> The film, which is Marvel's first superhero movie tentpole franchise with an Asian protagonist,<ref name=\"Deadline Marvel\" /> will star [[Simu Liu]] as the title character, with [[Tony Leung Chiu-wai]] and [[Awkwafina]] set to co-star.<ref name=\"Shang-ChiComic-Con\" /> In January 5, 2020, Cretton said that he signed up to the project because he wanted \"to give [his] son a superhero to look up to\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/just-mercy-shang-chi-why-destin-daniel-cretton-shifted-gears-marvels-superhero-film-1265402|title=From 'Just Mercy' to 'Shang-Chi': Why Destin Daniel Cretton Shifted Gears for Marvel's Superhero Film|website=Hollywood Reporter|first=Rebbeca|last=Ford|date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> The film will be released on February 12, 2021.<ref name=\"Shang-ChiComic-Con\" />  During the midst of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], Cretton self-isolated himself while awaiting [[COVID-19 testing|testing]] per the request of his doctor, which temporarily suspended first unit production for ''Shang-Chi'' in [[Australia]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-suspends-production-as-director-isolates-1284454</ref>  The test came back negative.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B90aKizJk9K/</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-right:0;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Director\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Writer\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Producer\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''I Am Not a Hipster''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Also editor\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Short Term 12]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Just Mercy]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2021\n| ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| Filming\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|2308774}}\n\n{{Destin Daniel Cretton}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cretton, Destin Daniel}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Slovak descent]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:American film editors]]\n[[Category:People from Maui]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Point Loma Nazarene University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Diego State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:American film directors of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Destin Daniel Cretton\n| image       = Destin Daniel Cretton by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption     = Cretton at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name   = <!--- Only included if birth name differs from article name --->\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1978|11|23}}\n| birth_place  = [[Haiku, Hawaii]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Featured Filmmaker: Destin Cretton, Writer/Director of 'Short Term 12\u2032|url=http://news.mauifilmfestival.net/2013/06/17/destin-cretton-short-term-12/|work=Maui Film Festival|accessdate=July 9, 2014|date=June 17, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113222801/http://news.mauifilmfestival.net/2013/06/17/destin-cretton-short-term-12/|archivedate=2017-11-13|url-status=dead|last=Tekula|first=Sara}}</ref>\n| alma_mater = [[Point Loma Nazarene University]]<br />[[San Diego State University]]\n| occupation  = Film director, screenwriter, producer, editor\n| years_active = 2002\u2013present\n| spouse(s) = Nikki Chapman\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''Destin Daniel Cretton''' (born November 23, 1978)<ref>{{cite web|title=United States Public Records Index|url=https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/2S5M-3ZY|work=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> is an American film director, screenwriter, producer, and editor. He is best known for his collaborations with [[Brie Larson]], in the films ''[[Short Term 12]]'' (2013), ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]]'' (2017), and ''[[Just Mercy]]'' (2019).\n\n== Early life ==\nCretton was born in 1978 in [[Haiku, Hawaii]] on the island of [[Maui]], the son of Janice Harue Cretton, a [[Japanese American]] hairdresser, and Daniel Cretton, of [[Irish American|Irish]] and [[Slovak American|Slovak]] ancestry, who worked for the fire department.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/alisonwillmore/28-asian-american-filmakers|title=28 Asian-American Filmmakers You Need To Know|first=Alison|last=Willmore|website=BuzzFeed|date=May 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nichibei.org/2018/01/the-great-unknown-and-the-unknown-great-cinematic-20th-century-nikkei/|title=THE GREAT UNKNOWN AND THE UNKNOWN GREAT: Cinematic 20th century Nikkei \u00bb Nichi Bei|website=www.nichibei.org|date=January 1, 2018|last=Robinson|first=Greg }}</ref> He was home-schooled by his Christian mother.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://hanahou.com/16.5/moving-pictures|title=Moving Pictures|website=Hana Hou!|issue=16.5|last=Wianecki|first=Shannon|date=October\u2013November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mauinews.com/news/local-news/2017/08/filmmaker-recalls-his-haiku-past-while-directing-the-glass-castle/|title=Filmmaker recalls his Haiku past while directing \u2018The Glass Castle\u2019|website=The Maui News|publisher=|last=Sugidono|first=Chris|date=August 11, 2017}}</ref> He lived in Haiku in a two-bedroom house with his five siblings,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Valentini |first1=Valentina |title=Director Destin Daniel Cretton Has Always Lived in The Glass Castle |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/08/the-glass-castle-destin-daniel-cretton-brie-larson-jeannette-walls-short-term-12 |work=Vanity Fair |date=August 8, 2017}}</ref> including sister Joy, until he was 19 years old. He moved to [[San Diego]], [[California]] to attend [[Point Loma Nazarene University]], where he majored in [[communications]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldstein|first=Jessica|title='Short Term 12' writer-director Destin Daniel Cretton on real-life inspiration behind his film|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/short-term-12-writer-director-destin-daniel-cretton-on-real-life-inspiration-behind-his-film/2013/08/28/e0025ebc-0e6e-11e3-bdf6-e4fc677d94a1_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=February 5, 2014|date=August 30, 2013}}</ref> After graduating, Cretton worked for two years as a staff person at a group home for at-risk teenagers.<ref name=\"IW\">{{cite web|title=Meet the 2013 SXSW Filmmakers #30: 'Hipster' Destin Daniel Cretton Returns With Brie Larson Starring Drama 'Short Term 12'|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/meet-the-2013-sxsw-filmmakers-52|work=[[Indiewire]]|accessdate=February 5, 2014|date=March 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Adams|first=Sam|title=Short Term 12 filmmaker Destin Cretton|url=http://thedissolve.com/features/emerging/105-destin-cretton/|work=The Dissolve|accessdate=February 5, 2014|date=August 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe made short films as a hobby, which developed as a vocational path. He attended and graduated from film school at [[San Diego State University]].<ref name=\"IW\" />\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Destin Daniel Cretton cropped.jpg|thumb|Cretton at the [[Deauville American Film Festival]] in 2013|alt=|left|207x207px]]\nWhile at San Diego State University, Cretton made a 22-minute short film, ''Short Term 12'', based on his experiences at the facility for teenagers. The short film premiered at the [[2009 Sundance Film Festival]], where it won the Jury Prize in Short Filmmaking.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/short-term-12-writer-director-destin-daniel-cretton-on-real-life-inspiration-behind-his-film/2013/08/28/e0025ebc-0e6e-11e3-bdf6-e4fc677d94a1_story.html|title=\u2018Short Term 12\u2019 writer-director Destin Daniel Cretton on real-life inspiration behind his film|last=Goldstein|first=Jessica|date=August 31, 2013|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from film school, Cretton decided to adapt the short into a feature-length screenplay, which won one of the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]' five [[Nicholl Fellowships in Screenwriting]] in 2010.<ref name=\"viva\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.vivaverve.com/shopimages/documents/ST12%20Production%20Notes.pdf|title=Short Term 12|publisher=Verve Pictures|year=2013|accessdate=April 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThat screenplay served as the basis for what would become the [[Short Term 12|feature film of the same name]], also directed by Cretton, which was released in 2013.<ref name=\"SDCB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sdcitybeat.com/sandiego/article-12161-the-rise-of-destin-daniel-cretton.html|title=The rise of Destin Daniel Cretton|last=Bradford|first=Ryan|date=September 4, 2013|work=San Diego City Beat|publisher=[[Southland Publishing]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222135924/http://www.sdcitybeat.com/sandiego/article-12161-the-rise-of-destin-daniel-cretton.html|archive-date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=February 5, 2014}}</ref> The film premiered on March 10, 2013 at [[South by Southwest]], where it won the Grand Jury and Audience Awards for a Narrative Feature.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/film/global/memento-rolls-out-short-term-12-exclusive-1200576825/|title=Memento Rolls Out \u2018Short Term 12\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Hopewell|first=John|date=August 11, 2013|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=April 22, 2014}}</ref> Widely acclaimed as one of the best films of 2013, it was listed on many film critics' annual top ten lists.<ref name=\"acclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critic-top-10-lists-best-movies-of-2013|title=Film Critic Top 10 Lists - Best Movies of 2013|work=Metacritic|accessdate=March 10, 2019}}</ref> The film earned several accolades, including three [[Independent Spirit Award]] nominations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/03/01/indie-spirit-awards-2014-winners-list/|title=Independent Spirit Awards 2014: The winners list|last=Atkinson|first=Katie|date=March 1, 2014|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Cretton was attached to rewrite the script and direct ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]]'', an adaptation of [[Jeannette Walls]]' [[The Glass Castle|2005 best-selling memoir of the same name]] about a successful young woman raised by severely dysfunctional parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/jennifer-lawrences-glass-castle-gains-momentum-at-lionsgate-1201278534/|title = Jennifer Lawrence's 'Glass Castle' Gains Momentum at Lionsgate|last = McNary|first = Dave|website = Variety|language = en-US|date=August 8, 2014|access-date = 2016-03-26}}</ref> Starring Larson, the film also features [[Woody Harrelson]] and [[Naomi Watts]] as her alcoholic father and eccentric mother, respectively.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/naomi-watts-talks-join-brie-878672|title=Naomi Watts in Talks to Join Brie Larson in Drama 'Glass Castle' (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=2016-03-29|access-date=2016-03-30}}</ref> Larson's role was originally considered by [[Jennifer Lawrence]], but she dropped out while the studio was seeking the male lead.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://deadline.com/2015/11/woody-harrelson-the-glass-castle-opposite-brie-larson-1201609016/|title = Woody Harrelson in Talks For 'The Glass Castle' Opposite Brie Larson|last = Busch|first = Anita|website = Deadline|language = en-US|date=November 5, 2015|access-date = 2016-03-26}}</ref> The film was released on August 10, 2017.<ref name=\":0\" /> It received mixed reviews from critics; they praised the performances of its cast (particularly Larson and Harrelson) but criticized the emotional tones and adaptation of the source material.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/annabelle-creation-is-a-potent-prequel/|title=Annabelle: Creation is a Potent Prequel|last=Giles|first=Jeff|date=August 10, 2017|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, it was announced that [[Ryan Coogler]] had teamed up with Cretton and poet/playwright [[Chinaka Hodge]] to develop ''Minors'', a new television drama series produced by Charles D. King. Drawing from Cretton's experiences working in residential foster care, Hodge's background teaching under-served youth in San Francisco Bay area continuation schools, and Coogler's upbringing in the East Bay, ''Minors'' promises to take an unflinching look at institutionalization, exploring juvenile facilities and the children who grow up in that system. The series will show how that system shapes young people over a one-year period. Hodge will write the series, and Coogler and Cretton will direct.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://deadline.com/2016/02/creed-director-ryan-coogler-developing-series-drama-minors-1201709611/|title = Ryan Coogler Teams With Destin Daniel Cretton & Chinaka Hodge For TV Drama 'Minors'|last = Lincoln|first = Ross A.|website = Deadline|language = en-US|date=February 25, 2016|access-date = 2016-03-25}}</ref>\n\nCretton subsequently teamed with Larson and [[Michael B. Jordan]] for ''[[Just Mercy]]'', a drama film based on civil rights defense attorney [[Bryan Stevenson]]'s ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' bestselling memoir: ''Just Mercy: A Story of Justice and Redemption.''<ref name=\"Deadline Marvel\">{{Cite web|url = https://deadline.com/2019/03/destin-creston-shang-chi-marvel-choice-1202575136/|title = Destin Daniel Cretton Marvel\u2019s Choice To Direct \u2018Shang-Chi\u2019|website = Deadline|last=Fleming Jr.|first=Mike|date=March 13, 2019|language = en-US|access-date = 2019-04-19}}</ref> Stevenson founded the Equal Justice Institute in Montgomery, Alabama, where he provided defense counsel to men on death row. The plot follows Stevenson (Jordan) as he explores the case of a death row prisoner, [[Walter McMillian]], whom he fought to free.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://deadline.com/2018/08/brie-larson-michael-b-jordan-just-mercy-destin-cretton-warner-bros-1202442881/|title = Brie Larson In Talks To Join Michael B. Jordan In \u2018Just Mercy\u2019|author=Denise Petski, Dino-Ray Ramos|date=August 8, 2018|website = Deadline|language = en-US|access-date = 2019-04-19}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 6, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/|title=Toronto Film Festival: 'Joker,' 'Ford v Ferrari,' 'Hustlers' Among Big Premieres|last=Lang|first=Brent|date=July 23, 2019|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=July 23, 2019}}</ref> and was theatrically released on December 25, 2019, by [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]. ''Just Mercy'' was critically acclaimed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michael-b-jordans-just-mercy-lands-year-end-awards-release-sesame-street-pushed-1224638|title=Michael B. Jordan's 'Just Mercy' Lands Year-End Awards Release; 'Sesame Street' Officially Pushed|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Cretton was hired by [[Marvel Studios]] to direct a film based on [[Shang-Chi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-sets-director-destin-daniel-cretton-1194443|title=Marvel's 'Shang-Chi' Sets Director Destin Daniel Cretton|website=Hollywood Reporter|first1=Borys |last1=Kit|first2=Aaron |last2=Couch|date=March 13, 2019|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}</ref> Both the film and Cretton's involvement were confirmed during the [[San Diego Comic-Con]] 2019, with the film being titled ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]''.<ref name=\"Shang-ChiComic-Con\">{{cite web|url= https://variety.com/2019/film/news/simu-liu-marvels-shang-chi-1203268497/|first= Justin|last= Kroll|title= Marvel's ''Shang-Chi'' Finds Its Lead|work= Variety|date= July 20, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190721174008/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/simu-liu-marvels-shang-chi-1203268497/|archivedate= July 21, 2019|url-status= live|df= mdy-all|access-date= July 20, 2019}}</ref> The film, which is Marvel's first superhero movie tentpole franchise with an Asian protagonist,<ref name=\"Deadline Marvel\" /> will star [[Simu Liu]] as the title character, with [[Tony Leung Chiu-wai]] and [[Awkwafina]] set to co-star.<ref name=\"Shang-ChiComic-Con\" /> In January 5, 2020, Cretton said that he signed up to the project because he wanted \"to give [his] son a superhero to look up to\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/just-mercy-shang-chi-why-destin-daniel-cretton-shifted-gears-marvels-superhero-film-1265402|title=From 'Just Mercy' to 'Shang-Chi': Why Destin Daniel Cretton Shifted Gears for Marvel's Superhero Film|website=Hollywood Reporter|first=Rebbeca|last=Ford|date=January 5, 2020}}</ref> The film will be released on February 12, 2021.<ref name=\"Shang-ChiComic-Con\" />  During the midst of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], Cretton self-isolated himself while awaiting [[COVID-19 testing|testing]] per the request of his doctor, which temporarily suspended first unit production for ''Shang-Chi'' in [[Australia]] on March 12, 2020.<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-suspends-production-as-director-isolates-1284454</ref>  The test came back negative.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B90aKizJk9K/</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-right:0;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Director\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Writer\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Producer\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''I Am Not a Hipster''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Also editor\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Short Term 12]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Glass Castle (film)|The Glass Castle]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Just Mercy]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2021\n| ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| Filming\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|2308774}}\n\n{{Destin Daniel Cretton}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cretton, Destin Daniel}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Slovak descent]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:American film editors]]\n[[Category:People from Maui]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Point Loma Nazarene University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Diego State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Asian-American film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n", "name_user": "Myasuda", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:refined category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Destin_Daniel_Cretton"}
{"title_page": "Wayne Garfield", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Wayne Garfield\n| image       = \n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = \n| residence   = \n| nationality = United States\n| education   = \n| occupation  = songwriter, vocalist, producer\n| spouse      = \n| partner     =\n| children    = \n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes   =\n}}\n\n'''Wayne Garfield''' is a composer, collaborating songwriter, vocalist, social entrepreneur, community activists, and producer for four decades. He is a contributor, and co founder of the vaunted music collective [[Change (band)]], contributing to musical pop culture. Chance launched the career of [[Luther Vandross]] with the hit song \"[[The Glow of Love]]\". Which became #1 on the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] Dance/Disco Chart in the summer of 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiritmusicgroup.com/Clients/Library/Wayne-Garfield|title=Spirit Music Group &#124; Wayne Garfield|website=www.spiritmusicgroup.com|accessdate=Apr 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924170725/http://www.spiritmusicgroup.com/Clients/Library/Wayne-Garfield|archive-date=September 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.writersrulecoalition.org/about_us|title=FOUNDER|website=Wrc200|accessdate=Apr 13, 2020}}</ref> <ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=NMSKDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT70&ots=IfmS4-buYF&dq=wayne%20garfield%20vocalist&pg=PT70#v=onepage&q=wayne%20garfield%20&f=false</ref><ref>https://www.loc.gov/item/jots.200014575</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGarfield's career started as a singer with the [[The Voices of East Harlem]] a rock and soul group. The group was formed in 1969 in Harlem, New York City.  The group recorded with [[Elektra Records|Elektra]], Just Sunshine, and [[Motown]]. The Voices of East Harlem was a 20-member ensemble aged 12 to 21. The group worked with producers [[Leroy Hutson]] and [[Curtis Mayfield]]. \nGarfield was a member of the [[Change (band)]] collected. He has composed music for [[Janet Jackson]], [[Luther Vandross]], [[Roy Ayers]], [[Kurtis Blow]], [[Taj Mahal]], [[Dee Dee Bridgewater]],  soundtrack for the movie Coffy, Salt-N-Pepa, [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Theo Croker]], and [[Fela Kuti]]. He has functioned in the capacity of composer, lyricist, manager and arranger for three decades. In 1973 Garfield wrote the soundtrack and vocals for the movie [[Coffy]]. The movie was directed by [[Jack Hill]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secondhandsongs.com/artist/19425|title=Songs written by Wayne Garfield &#124; SecondHandSongs|website=secondhandsongs.com|accessdate=Apr 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tidal.com/browse/artist/6739475|title=Wayne Garfield|website=TIDAL Browse|accessdate=Apr 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe has worked with [[Angela Winbush]] and Debye Burrell to develop their careers.\n\nGarfield has worked with Carl Clay and he is one of the co-founders of Black Spectrum Theater in South Jamaica Queens, New York City. The theatre was founded in 1970s. <ref>https://www.newyorksaid.com/carl-clay-black-spectrum-theatre-interview/</ref>\n\nIn 1986 Garfield united [[Kurtis Blow]] and [[Bob Dylan]] in producing \"Street Rock\", which became a hip-hop crossover.\n\nIn 2002,  Garfield formed the advocacy group \"Writers Rule Coalition\", for songwriters to gain award recognition.\n\nIn 2003, the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences Board of Trustees awarded the Winners Certificate to songwriters and producers of Grammy nominated and winning recordings containing samples. Which gave writers and producers recognition for their contribution.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Composer===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* 2019\tEverything and More: The Complete Collection 1980\u20132019; (Change Collective) \t\n* 2018\tKOD; J. Cole\t\n* 2016\tEscape Velocity; Theo Croker\t\n* 2014\tThe Box Set Series; Luther Vandross\t\n* 2013\t12\" Disco: The Collection\t\t\n* 20