.org/fathers/timothy_i_apology_00_intro.htm Intro] and [http://www.tertullian.org/fathers/timothy_i_apology_01_text.htm translation]\n* [http://etd.ohiolink.edu/send-pdf.cgi/Hackenburg%20Clint.pdf?osu1245399770 The religious debate between Timothy I and the Caliph al-Mahd\u012b] Arabic text with English translation by Clint Hackenburg, 2009\n* [https://archive.org/details/detimotheoinesto00labo De Timotheo I, Nestorianorum patriacha, et Christianorum orientalium condicione sub chaliphis Abbasidis] by J\u00e9r\u00f4me Labourt, 1904\n* Timothy I, Letters : [https://archive.org/details/EpitulaeTimotheiISyriac syriac text] and  [https://archive.org/details/EpistulaeTimotheiILatin Latin translation] by  O. Braun, 1915\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{succession box\n |before=[[Hnanisho II|Hnanisho{{transl|ar|DIN|\u02bf}} II]]<br>(773\u2013780)\n |title=[[List of Patriarchs of the Church of the East|Catholicus-Patriarch of the East]]\n |years=(780\u2013823)\n |after=[[Isho Bar Nun|Isho{{transl|ar|DIN|\u02bf}} Bar Nun]]<br>(823\u2013828)\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Patriarchs of the Church of the East}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Timothy 1}}\n[[Category:823 deaths]]\n[[Category:Patriarchs of the Church of the East]]\n[[Category:Christian apologists]]\n[[Category:Nestorians in the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Greek\u2013Syriac translators]]\n[[Category:Syriac\u2013Arabic translators]]\n[[Category:8th-century people of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:9th-century people of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:9th-century Syriac-language writers]]\n", "name_user": "Srnec", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInterest in missionary expansion:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timothy_I_(Nestorian_patriarch)"}
{"title_page": "Roderick Jones (1877\u20131962)", "text_new": "{{For|others of the same name|Roderick Jones}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Roderick Jones\n| image       = Roderick Jones.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = George Roderick Jones\n| birth_date  = 21 October 1877\n| birth_place = [[Dukinfield]], [[Cheshire]]\n| death_date  = 23 January 1962\n| death_place = 29, [[Hyde Park Gate]], [[Westminster]]\n| nationality = English \n| other_names = \n| occupation  = Journalist, later head of [[Reuters]]\n| known_for   = \n}}\n\nSir '''George Roderick Jones''' (21 October 1877 \u2013 23 January 1962) was a British journalist and news agency manager, who for most of his career worked for [[Reuters]]. From 1916, he was a significant shareholder in the company.\n\n==Life==\nJones was born in [[Dukinfield]], [[Cheshire]], the only son of Roderick Patrick Jones, a [[Manchester]] hat salesman, by his marriage to Christina Drennan Gibb.<ref name=odnb>[[Donald Read]], [https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/34227 Jones, Sir (George) Roderick (1877\u20131962), news agency director], in [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] (Oxford University Press, 2004) online, accessed 15 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> His parents had been married at St Saviour\u2019s church, Manchester, on 13 September 1877, barely a month before his birth. His father was then a salesman, and his grandfather, John Jones, a butcher.<ref>[https://www.ancestry.co.uk/interactive/2962/40364_636672_2203-00033 Register of Marriages, p. 52], at ancestry.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894, Jones took up an invitation to join an aunt in [[Pretoria]], then in the [[South African Republic]]. In 1895, he took a job as sub-editor on the ''Pretoria Press'', and later that year became an assistant to the Reuters correspondent in the [[Transvaal]]. In 1896, Jones\u2019s interview with [[Leander Starr Jameson|Dr Jameson]] in the aftermath of the [[Jameson Raid]] was networked internationally.<ref name=odnb/> In 1905, he became general manager of the Reuters office for the Union of South Africa.<ref name=palmer>Michael B. Palmer, ''International News Agencies: A History'', p. 75</ref> \n\nIn April 1915, during the [[World War I|First World War]], the Reuters general manager in London, [[Herbert de Reuter|Baron Herbert de Reuter]], killed himself, a few days after his wife had died, and with the company in financial difficulties. In October 1915, Jones was appointed as general manager, and in 1916 he and the company chairman, Mark Napier, bought the company, with financial help from the British government.<ref name=palmer/> During the rest of the War, Reuters followed a carefully patriotic line, so much so that Jones was accused of being the British government's Head of Propaganda. He was knighted in 1918, in recognition of his services to journalism.<ref name=odnb/>\n\nJones became chairman of Reuters, as well as general manager, and retired from those posts in 1941.<ref name=odnb/> In 1951, [[Hodder & Stoughton]] published his autobiography ''A Life in Reuters''.<ref>Roderick Jones, ''A Life in Reuters'' (Hodder & Stoughton, 1951), {{ISBN|978-1125911136}}</ref>\n\nJones had a house at 29, [[Hyde Park Gate]], [[Westminster]], where he died on 23 January 1962, and he was buried at [[Rottingdean]], where he also had a home, North End House, previously owned by the artist [[Edward Burne-Jones]].<ref name=odnb/> An obituary in ''[[The Times]]'' said he had been one of only two or three leading figures in the world of news.<ref>\u201cObituary: Sir Roderick Jones, a Lifetime at Reuters\u201d in ''[[The Times]]'' (London), 24 January 1962, p. 15</ref> He left an estate valued at \u00a338,042, and probate was granted on 14 May to his daughter Laurian, Comtesse d\u2019Harcourt, wife of Comte Anne-Pierre d\u2019Harcourt.<ref name=probate>\u201cJONES sir George Roderick otherwise Sir Roderick K.B.E.\u201d in Probate Index for 1962, at probatesearch.service.gov.uk, accessed 15 April 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]] has portrait photographs of Jones by [[Alexander Bassano|Bassano]] and [[Walter Stoneman]].<ref>[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp78568/sir-george-roderick-jones Sir (George) Roderick Jones (1877-1962)] at [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], accessed 17 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1920, Jones married the author [[Enid Bagnold]], and they had four children.<ref name=odnb/> Their only daughter, Laurian, was born in 1921,<ref>\u201cJones Laurian / Bagnold\u201d in Register of Births for Lewisham, vol. 1D (1921), p. S'22</ref> and was married first, from 1952 to 1955, to [[Rowland Winn, 4th Baron St Oswald|Rowland Winn]],<ref>[http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/stoswald1885.htm Saint Oswald, Baron (UK, 1885)] at cracroftspeerage.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> and second to Anne-Pierre d\u2019Harcourt.<ref name=probate/> A son, Timothy Angus Jones, was born in 1924<ref>\u201cJones Timothy A / Bagnold\u201d in Register of Births for Woolwich, vol. 1d (1924), p. 1748</ref> and later married Patricia David Pandora Clifford, daughter of [[Bede Clifford|Sir Bede Clifford]],<ref>''[[Burke's Peerage]]'', vol. 1 (1999), p. 131</ref> becoming the father of [[Annabel Astor, Viscountess Astor|Annabel Astor]], who is the mother of [[Samantha Cameron]].<ref>Melonie Clarke, Helena Gumley-Mason, \u201dSamantha Cameron's Sari Diplomacy\u201d in ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]'', 26 November 2013, [https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195032/http://www.lady.co.uk/people/profiles/3336-samantha-cameron-s-sari-diplomacy archived here]</ref> A second son, Richard Bagnold Jones, was born in 1926 and became a writer on [[narrow-gauge railways]];<ref>\u201cJones Richard B / Bagnold\u201d in Register of Births for St. George Hanover Square, vol. 1a\t(1926), p. 584; [https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp67753/richard-bagnold-jones Richard Bagnold Jones] at [[National Gallery, London]], accessed 18 April 2020</ref> A third son, Dominick, was born in 1930.<ref>\u201dJones Dominick / Bagnold\u201d in Register of Births for Kensington, vol. 1a (1930), p. 156A</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n*[[Donald Read]], \u201dSir Roderick Jones and Reuters: Rise and Fall of a News Emperor\u201d, in D. Fraser, ed., ''Cities, Class and Communications, Essays in Honour of Asa Briggs'' (Harvester, 1990), pp. 175-99\n* Roderick Jones, ''A Life in Reuters'' (Hodder & Stoughton, 1951) {{ISBN|978-1125911136}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thebaron.info/archives/sir-roderick-joness-finest-hour Sir Roderick Jones\u2019s Finest Hour] at thebaron.info\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/identities/viaf-93722307/ Jones, Roderick Sir 1877-1962] at worldcat.org\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Roderick}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Dukinfield]]\n[[Category:Reuters people]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|others of the same name|Roderick Jones}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Roderick Jones\n| image       = Roderick Jones.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = George Roderick Jones\n| birth_date  = 21 October 1877\n| birth_place = [[Dukinfield]], [[Cheshire]]\n| death_date  = 23 January 1962\n| death_place = 29, [[Hyde Park Gate]], [[Westminster]]\n| nationality = English \n| other_names = \n| occupation  = Journalist, later head of [[Reuters]]\n| known_for   = \n}}\n\nSir '''George Roderick Jones''' (21 October 1877 \u2013 23 January 1962) was a British journalist and news agency manager, who for most of his career worked for [[Reuters]]. From 1916, he was a significant shareholder in the company.\n\n==Life==\nJones was born in [[Dukinfield]], [[Cheshire]], the only son of Roderick Patrick Jones, a [[Manchester]] hat salesman, by his marriage to Christina Drennan Gibb.<re