l manager, and retired from those posts in 1941.<ref name=odnb/> In 1951, [[Hodder & Stoughton]] published his autobiography ''A Life in Reuters''.<ref>Roderick Jones, ''A Life in Reuters'' (Hodder & Stoughton, 1951), {{ISBN|978-1125911136}}</ref>\n\nJones had a house at 29, [[Hyde Park Gate]], [[Westminster]], where he died on 23 January 1962, and he was buried at [[Rottingdean]], where he also had a home, North End House, previously owned by the artist [[Edward Burne-Jones]].<ref name=odnb/> An obituary in ''[[The Times]]'' said he had been one of only two or three leading figures in the world of news.<ref>\u201cObituary: Sir Roderick Jones, a Lifetime at Reuters\u201d in ''[[The Times]]'' (London), 24 January 1962, p. 15</ref> He left an estate valued at \u00a338,042, and probate was granted on 14 May to his daughter Laurian, Comtesse d\u2019Harcourt, wife of Comte Anne-Pierre d\u2019Harcourt.<ref name=probate>\u201cJONES sir George Roderick otherwise Sir Roderick K.B.E.\u201d in Probate Index for 1962, at probatesearch.service.gov.uk, accessed 15 April 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]] has portrait photographs of Jones by [[Alexander Bassano|Bassano]] and [[Walter Stoneman]].<ref>[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp78568/sir-george-roderick-jones Sir (George) Roderick Jones (1877-1962)] at [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], accessed 17 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1920, Jones married the author [[Enid Bagnold]], and they had four children.<ref name=odnb/> Their only daughter, Laurian, was born in 1921, and was married first, from 1952 to 1955, to [[Rowland Winn, 4th Baron St Oswald|Rowland Winn]],<ref>[http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/stoswald1885.htm Saint Oswald, Baron (UK, 1885)] at cracroftspeerage.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> and second to Anne-Pierre d\u2019Harcourt.<ref name=probate/> A son, Timothy Angus Jones, was born in 1924 and later married Patricia David Pandora Clifford, daughter of [[Bede Clifford|Sir Bede Clifford]],<ref>''[[Burke's Peerage]]'', vol. 1 (1999), p. 131</ref> becoming the father of [[Annabel Astor, Viscountess Astor|Annabel Astor]], who is the mother of [[Samantha Cameron]].<ref>Melonie Clarke, Helena Gumley-Mason, \u201dSamantha Cameron's Sari Diplomacy\u201d in ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]'', 26 November 2013, [https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195032/http://www.lady.co.uk/people/profiles/3336-samantha-cameron-s-sari-diplomacy archived here]</ref> A second son, Richard Bagnold Jones, was born in 1926 and became a writer on [[narrow-gauge railways]];<ref>\u201cJones Richard B / Bagnold\u201d in Register of Births for St. George Hanover Square, vol. 1a\t(1926), p. 584; [https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp67753/richard-bagnold-jones Richard Bagnold Jones] at [[National Gallery, London]], accessed 18 April 2020</ref><ref> \u201cJones Laurian / Bagnold\u201d in Register of Births for Lewisham, vol. 1D (1921), p. S'22; \u201cJones Timothy A / Bagnold\u201d in Register of Births for Woolwich, vol. 1d (1924), p. 1748.</ref> A third son, Dominick, was born in 1930.<ref>\u201dJones Dominick / Bagnold\u201d in Register of Births for Kensington, vol. 1a (1930), p. 156A</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n*[[Donald Read]], \u201dSir Roderick Jones and Reuters: Rise and Fall of a News Emperor\u201d, in D. Fraser, ed., ''Cities, Class and Communications, Essays in Honour of Asa Briggs'' (Harvester, 1990), pp. 175-99\n* Roderick Jones, ''A Life in Reuters'' (Hodder & Stoughton, 1951) {{ISBN|978-1125911136}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thebaron.info/archives/sir-roderick-joness-finest-hour Sir Roderick Jones\u2019s Finest Hour] at thebaron.info\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/identities/viaf-93722307/ Jones, Roderick Sir 1877-1962] at worldcat.org\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Roderick}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of th